text:
book name: #metoo brutus 
author : prana natarajan 
genre :fiction
self published
i was happy when the author prana natarajan pinged me asking if i can review his debut book. thanks pn for having the confidence in me and asking me to review your book.
"#metoo brutus" is a catchy title. really appreciate the author in having given a good thought about the title. we all have heard/read the #metoo stories going around in social media. this book is also about similar #metoo incidents that happened in the recent past, all woven into a nice story. 
the story is about few characters and their #metoo situations. one a studious girl and how her dreams are shattered, a mother getting abused by godman, another small town studious girl facing a #metoo situation and how she took a bold step to get the culprit under the law, another professional facing a #metoo situation at work place, a small girl facing a #metoo situation with godman. all these stories have a interwoven secret and the author has surely kept that as a suspense till the last. 
the other part of the book also speaks about how each of the #metoo victims deal with it and if the culprits are punished or not. 
being an indian background story a minister,a political power, sure does have an important role in the book. which is yet another surprise element in the story. 
the last bit of the story is an eye opener with awareness information. 
enjoyed reading the book and being a debut book the author has done a fair job. he already has his second manuscript ready and eagerly waiting to read that too. as of now available in kindle.

text: it is trite to say that knowledge is power, but consider this: slaveowners were free to poke, prod, impale and defile slaves in any manner they saw fit, but by law could not teach their slaves to read. this was the one prohibition concerning the slaveowner's treatment of his slaves. as a slave, douglass, risked his life by trading food for tutelage, but such is the thirst of the mind. although douglass was the 19th century's most photographed american, and among the most eloquent freedom fighters in all of history, he was also among america's first feminists. during the seneca falls convention in july 1848, douglass was the only man to advocate including women's suffrage in the convention's declaration of sentiments, a position so radical at the time it was thought to hurt the more immediate issue of abolition. for douglass, freedom and civil rights were not a matter of political timing, but of moral necessity. in the end, the suffrage provision was included, but the document was signed by just 100 of the convention's 300 attendees. following the death of his first wife, whose freedom he helped procure via the underground railroad, douglass fell in love and married a white woman, to the chagrin of many whites and blacks of his day. following emancipation, douglass served in several federal positions during reconstruction and was nominated for vice president in 1872 by the equal rights party, under victoria woodhull, the first female candidate for u.s. president. a lifelong teetotaler, douglass formed the first all-black temperance league and advocated a lifestyle consistent with what today we call recovery. though disowned by her family, douglass lived happily with his wife until he died in 1895.  #blackhistory #metoo #recoveryrevolution #recoverywarrior #greatamericans #freedom #knowledgeisgrowth #rudeboyintellect #recoveryispossible #teetotal #feminism #civilrights #readbooks #literacy
name: Rudeboy Recovery

text:
good morning everybody! as @whitneyysimmons would have said: it’s a beautiful day to be alive! ☀️. have you noticed that if you workout in the morning the people that are in the gym are usually very fit, like extremely fit, you know why? because they make the workout their priority, it’s the first thing they do, they make sure they do their workout early so that there can be no excuses later. don’t get me wrong i’m a night trainer as well, i love to workout in the evening and people that workout then are also in shape, but the level of those who fill the gym in the morning is next level. my point is, if you really want it, if you really want to turn things around, make sure to make them your priority, your numero uno on that list of yours and make sure you do it! if it so has to be the first thing you do in the morning 🌞 
rise and shine babes and enjoy your day 😘

text:
ce matin je lisais un article sur les phrases cultes de karl lagerfeld ... .voici donc une petite sélection "hommage" :
.
."ce sont les grosses bonnes femmes assises avec leur paquet de chips devant la télévision qui disent que les mannequins minces sont hideux "
.
. "j'aurais trouvé ça difficile d'avoir une fille laide"
.
. "les femmes rondes n'ont rien à faire sur les podiums"
.
. "une fille se plaint qu'il lui a tiré sur la culotte et il se fait aussitôt excommunier par une profession qui jusque-là le vénérait. on croit rêver. si vous ne voulez pas qu'on vous tire sur la culotte, ne devenez pas mannequin ! rejoignez plutôt l'union des ursulines." .
."l'anorexie n'est pas un vrai sujet, il y en a si peu"
.
.
je passe aussi les propos tenus récemment par yann moix . .
.
.
.tout ça pour dire qu'en tant que femme, peut-être mère d'une fille un jour, j'espère qu'on fera la paix avec nous-même et qu'on nous la fichera un peu par la même occasion ❤️❤️ bonne après-midi !

#woman #femme #mode #mysogynie #liberté #metoo #feminisme #women

text:
today’s #positivequoteoftheday💛 
life can often seem to put pressure on us to constantly do better and compare us to others. when we are at school there is pressure to get good grades and classes named “top set”. in the workplace there is often performance related pay, targets, pressure to be the best colleague.

all this does for some is destroy their self esteem and confidence as despite always doing their best they will never be “top set”. yet they will be awesome and brilliant in other ways not recognised by the systems.

text:
阿部恭子さんの"家族という呪い"
阿部さんの著書を読んだのは二作目でしょうか。加害者家族をテーマにしています。
やはり今回も家族の内の誰かが罪を犯してしまったその実態に迫る一冊。
一番脳裏に浮かぶのは男性も性被害を受けているのだから、男性版のmetoo運動があってもいいという話。
決して差別云々ではないけれども女性のムーブメントに隠れてしまっている気もします。
決して一人もないがしろにしない社会を作りたいね！

text:
- c h a s s e  a u x  s o r c i e r e s -

lire absolument : la puissance invaincue des femmes, de mona chollet (les extraits viennent de cet ouvrage)

climat de terreur, qu’on situe souvent au moyen âge, commençant vers 1400 et continuant à la renaissance. des exécutions ont encore lieu à la fin du xviiie siècle. ce qui fait une assez longue période ! et ce n’est pas forcément l’apanage des religieux. 
derrière le qualificatif de sorcière, ces tueries de masses visent les femmes. pour éviter qu’elles ne prennent trop de liberté, qu’elles n’en disent trop, éliminer une potentielle perturbatrice (une femme qui se serait fait violer et qui essayerait de faire éclater la vérité, se verrait traiter de « sorcière » et brûlée) « son bilan en vies humaines reste très discutée et ne sera probablement jamais établi avec certitude. dans les années 1970, on évoquait un million de victimes, voire bien plus. aujourd’hui, on parle plutôt de cinquante ou cent mille. n’y sont pas incluses celles qui ont été lynchées, ni celles qui se sont suicidées ou qui sont mortes en prison, soit des suites de la torture, soit en raison de leurs conditions de détention sordides. » p.22 
on en a fait du chemin… entre les #balancetonporc #metoo de ces dernières années ! pourtant, notre vigilance ne doit pas se relâcher. 
il y aura toujours des boucs émissaires que des extrêmes utiliseront pour tenter de rendre légitime la violence, pour cristalliser les douleurs du peuple en haine, les diriger vers des actes d’exclusion et une individualisation plus poussée… il ne faut pas se tromper « [ces chasses] illustrent d’abord l’entêtement des sociétés à désigner régulièrement un bouc émissaire à leurs malheurs, et à s’enfermer dans une spirale d’irrationalité, inaccessibles à toute argumentation sensée, jusqu’à ce que l’accumulation des discours de haine et une hostilité devenue obsessionnelle justifient le passage à la violence physique, perçue comme une légitime défense du corps social. (…) la diabolisation des femmes qualifiées de sorcières eut d’ailleurs beaucoup en commun avec l’antisémistisme. » p.14

#sorcières #chasseauxsorcières
#monachollet
#femmes
#politique
#société
#balancethetrue

text:
w i t c h  h u n t -
war on women 
climate of terror, during the middle ages, beginning around 1400 and continuing to the renaissance. executions are still taking place at the end of the 18th century. which is a long time! and these acts are not necessarily the prerogative of religious people…

behind this qualification, witch, these mass killings are aimed at women. why ? to avoid a reassessment of the established patriachal system, to avoid that women take too much liberty, so they can’t say too much, to eliminate potential disruptive (a woman who would have been violated and that would try to bring the truth to light, would be accused of being a "witch" and burned). to know more : kristen j. sollee, witches, sluts, feminists. conjuring the sex positive, threel media, los angeles, 2017
williams, selma r. riding the nightmare: women & witchcraft from the old world to colonial salem. new york: harper perennial, 1978.

text:
c h a s s e  a u x  s o r c i e r e s -

lire absolument : la puissance invaincue des femmes, de mona chollet (les extraits viennent de cet ouvrage)

climat de terreur, qu’on situe souvent au moyen âge, commençant vers 1400 et continuant à la renaissance. des exécutions ont encore lieu à la fin du xviiie siècle. ce qui fait une assez longue période ! et ce n’est pas forcément l’apanage des religieux. « comme souvent, la désignation du bouc émissaire, loin d’être le fait d’une populace grossière, est venue d’en haut, des classes cultivées. la naissance du mythe de la sorcière coïncide à peu près avec celle - en 1454 - de l’imprimerie, qui y a joué un rôle essentiel. » p.15 
derrière le qualificatif de sorcière, ces tueries de masses visent les femmes. pour éviter qu’elles ne prennent trop de liberté, qu’elles n’en disent trop, éliminer une potentielle perturbatrice (une femme qui se serait fait violer et qui essayerait de faire éclater la vérité, se verrait traiter de « sorcière » et brûlée) « plus largement, cependant, toute tête féminine qui dépassait pouvait susciter des vocations de chasseur de sorcières. répondre à un voisin, parler haut, avoir un fort caractère ou une sexualité un peu trop libre, être une gêneuse d’une quelconque manière suffisait à vous mettre en danger » p.17

on en a fait du chemin… entre les #balancetonporc #metoo de ces dernières années ! pourtant, notre vigilance ne doit pas se relâcher. 
il y aura toujours des boucs émissaires que des extrêmes utiliseront pour tenter de rendre légitime la violence, pour cristalliser les douleurs du peuple en haine, les diriger vers des actes d’exclusion et une individualisation plus poussée… il ne faut pas se tromper d’adversaire.

#monachollet
#femmes
#politique
#société
#balancethetrue
#antisemitisme
#racisme
#civilisation
#granddebatnational
#versunesocieteeclairee
#quandlepasseeclairelepresent

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
setiap orang berhak mendapatkan rasa
aman atas bentuk tubuh dan ekspresi gender, begitu pula dengan cara berpakaian dan ekspresi tubuh yang
lain. oleh karenanya pelabelan negatif seperti gambar diatas merupakan bentuk pelecehan seksual.

tidak ada "perempuan nakal, binal, bispak, sundal"!! dalam lingkungan masyarakat yang masih patriarkis, kita sering mendengar pelabelan negatif (stereotype) tersebut. perempuan yang mendapat stereotip seperti ini lebih rentan terhadap tindak pelecehan, karena masyarakat sendiri bahkan membenarkan tindak pelecehan terhadap perempuan yang mereka labeli demikian.

stereotype tersebut salah dan tidak dapat dijadikan landasan bagi siapapun untuk membenarkan tindak pelecehan seksual terhadap orang lain. label "perempuan baik-baik" ataupun "nakal, binal, bispak, sundal" adalah cerminan konstruksi sosial yang tidak setara, merupakan bentuk penghakiman moral dan kontrol terhadap tubuh perempuan.

text:
0120﻿
한 / 中﻿﻿
﻿﻿
#카멜표류기 part.3﻿
﻿
이번은 제가 3번째로 촬영에 참여했습니다. 이번에도 큰 맘 먹어서 나왔습니다. 욕 많이 먹을 것 같아서...오늘 본 영화는 2004년에 경상남도 밀양시에서 발생한 여중생 집단 성폭행 소건을 바탕으로 만들어진 '한공주'란 작품입니다. 이 사건은 총 41명의 가해자가 피해자 1명을 거의 1년동안에 100번 넘을 정도로 성폭행을 했습니다. 이 사건이 밝히고 나서 가해자들도 벌을 제대로 받지 않고 아무렇지 않게 살고 있는데 피해자는 여전히 어렵고 힘들게 지내고 있습니다. 우리가 이 영화를 통해서 대만과 한국의 미투운동 그리고 여성인권을 토의했습니다.﻿
﻿
일단은 이 작품이 사실보다는 이미 더 함축적인 표현과 방식으로 찍었더라도 영화를 봤던 과정에는 제가 무거움과 불편함을 많이 느겼습니다. 실제 상황을 보면 경찰들이 고문으로 피해자한테 '2차 가해'를 줬습니다. 피해자가 여성경찰로 중요부위의 상처를 검사해달라고 요구했는데 거부를 받았고 심지어는 남성경찰들이 피해자한테 '니가 저사람들을 꼬신거아냐?' '니가 진짜 밀양시의 치욕이다'고 등등 들어줄 수가 없는 말들을 많이 했습니다. 한국 지금은 어떻게 하는지 모르겠지만 제가 아는 대만 학생 성폭행 사건으로 얘기하자면 우선 조사할때는 여성경찰로 피해자랑 대화할겁니다. 그 다음에 사회국(社會局)이라고 하는 국가기관이 사공(社工, 사화공작사 社會工作師)을 피해자한테 보내줘서 심리적이나 법적인 상담 다  도와줄겁니다. 혹시나 성폭행의 가해자가 가족이라면 일단 피해자를 다른 데로 옮겨질겁니다. ﻿
﻿
여자주인공이 영화에서 '전 잘못한 게 없는데'라고 얘기했습니다. 이 한마디로 우리 지금 사는 이 사화가 피해자들을 얼마나 검토하는지 완전하게 털어놓았습니다. '니가 너무 야하게 입어서 그런거야' '니 사생활이 너무 지저분해서 그런거야' 이런 비판들 자주 들을 수 있는데 사실은 그렇지 않습니다. 벨기에 브뤼셀에 '당시에 당신은 무엇을 입었나요?(what were you wearing?)'라는 전시회가 있었습니다. 이 전시회의 내용은 성폭행 받었던 피해자들이 사건 발생했을 때는 입었던 옷으로 전시한 것입니다. 그럼 피해자들 당시에 다 어떤 옷을 입었는가? 바로 청바지, 티셔츠, 교복, 유니폼 등등, 이런 옷들 솔직히 야한 옷도 아닌데 다 아주 흔한 거잖아요? 그럼, 왜 피해자가 반성해야 하는지 이해가 안 됩니다.﻿
﻿
여성인권운동과 성평등운동의 발전은 이미 오래되었는데 지금까지는 사람들이 역시 항상 전통적인 생각과 규칙으로 남여성들을 제한을 합니다. 남자는 그래야 되고 여자는 저래야 되고 여전히 서로서로 상처를 계속 주고 있습니다. 직장에서도 유리 천장이 많이 남아있습니다. 얼마전에는 '대만은 세계 성평등 순위 8위를 땄다' 이런 기사가 나왔는데 제가 진짜 깜짝 놀랐습니다. 왜냐하면 대만 같은 상황은 성차별 문제 아직 심각하게 존재하고 있는데 그렇다면 다른 나라들은 상태가 얼마나 안 좋은지는 상상하지도 못 합니다. 멀지 않은 미래에서 성별과 성적 지향을 막론하고 서로서로 존경을 주고 권력도 평등하게 행사할 수 있으면 좋겠다고 성교육도 제대로 시켜야 더 이상 이런 비극을 없어질 수가 있다고 생각합니다. 그리고 대만은 어제 혼인평권(婚姻平權, 동성결혼) 초안 이미 나왔습니다. 먼저 모든 동성애자 커플들한테 축하드립니다. 꼭 행복하세요!!﻿
﻿
촬영 끝나고 나서 우리가 같이 '금색삼맥'이라는 맥주식당 갔습니다. 대만사람인데 저도 처음으로 먹으러 갔습니다. 맥주 전문집이라 맥주 역시 상큼하고 향기가 좋습니다. 다른 음식들도 되게 맛있습니다. 2분 덕분에 배터지게 먹었습니다. 감사합니다. ﻿
﻿﻿
#駱駝漂流記 part.3﻿
﻿
這次是我第三次參與拍攝，這次也是下了很大的決心才出演的，因為好像會被很多人罵哈哈哈。今天我們所觀賞的電影名為「青春勿語（原文直譯：韓公主）」，是改編自2004年在慶尚南道密陽市所發生的女學生集體性侵事件的作品。在這個事件中，41位的加害人在近乎一年期間對被害人進行了超過100次的性侵行為。在事件爆發之後，加害人們並沒有得到相對的懲罰，反而就像什麼事也沒發生的生活，而被害人則到目前為止都還非常辛苦地活著。我們透過這部電影來探討了台韓的女權及metoo運動。﻿
﻿
首先，雖然這部作品已經用了比事實相對隱晦的表現手法來拍攝，但在觀看的過程中我仍然感到非常沉重以及不適。而實際的狀況中，警察們在做筆錄時，給與了被害者不少的「二次加害」。 (太長了，留言繼續。너무 길어서 댓글로 할게요)

'니가 진짜 밀양시의 치욕이다'고 등등 들어줄 수가 없는 말들을 많이 했습니다. 한국 지금은 어떻게 하는지 모르겠지만 제가 아는 대만 학생 성폭행 사건으로 얘기하자면 우선 조사할때는 여성경찰로 피해자랑 대화할겁니다. 그 다음에 사회국(社會局)이라고 하는 국가기관이 사공(社工, 사화공작사 社會工作師)을 피해자한테 보내줘서 심리적이나 법적인 상담 다  도와줄겁니다. 혹시나 성폭행의 가해자가 가족이라면 일단 피해자를 다른 데로 옮겨질겁니다. ﻿
﻿
여자주인공이 영화에서 '전 잘못한 게 없는데'라고 얘기했습니다. 이 한마디로 우리 지금 사는 이 사화가 피해자들을 얼마나 검토하는지 완전하게 털어놓았습니다. '니가 너무 야하게 입어서 그런거야' '니 사생활이 너무 지저분해서 그런거야' 이런 비판들 자주 들을 수 있는데 사실은 그렇지 않습니다. 벨기에 브뤼셀에 '당시에 당신은 무엇을 입었나요?(what were you wearing?)'라는 전시회가 있었습니다. 이 전시회의 내용은 성폭행 받었던 피해자들이 사건 발생했을 때는 입었던 옷으로 전시한 것입니다. 그럼 피해자들 당시에 다 어떤 옷을 입었는가? 바로 청바지, 티셔츠, 교복, 유니폼 등등, 이런 옷들 솔직히 야한 옷도 아닌데 다 아주 흔한 거잖아요? 그럼, 왜 피해자가 반성해야 하는지 이해가 안 됩니다.﻿
﻿
여성인권운동과 성평등운동의 발전은 이미 오래되었는데 지금까지는 사람들이 역시 항상 전통적인 생각과 규칙으로 남여성들을 제한을 합니다. 남자는 그래야 되고 여자는 저래야 되고 여전히 서로서로 상처를 계속 주고 있습니다. 직장에서도 유리 천장이 많이 남아있습니다. 얼마전에는 '대만은 세계 성평등 순위 8위를 땄다' 이런 기사가 나왔는데 제가 진짜 깜짝 놀랐습니다. 왜냐하면 대만 같은 상황은 성차별 문제 아직 심각하게 존재하고 있는데 그렇다면 다른 나라들은 상태가 얼마나 안 좋은지는 상상하지도 못 합니다. 멀지 않은 미래에서 성별과 성적 지향을 막론하고 서로서로 존경을 주고 권력도 평등하게 행사할 수 있으면 좋겠다고 성교육도 제대로 시켜야 더 이상 이런 비극을 없어질 수가 있다고 생각합니다. 그리고 대만은 어제 혼인평권(婚姻平權, 동성결혼) 초안 이미 나왔습니다. 먼저 모든 동성애자 커플들한테 축하드립니다. 꼭 행복하세요!!﻿
﻿
촬영 끝나고 나서 우리가 같이 '금색삼맥'이라는 맥주식당 갔습니다. 대만사람인데 저도 처음으로 먹으러 갔습니다. 맥주 전문집이라 맥주 역시 상큼하고 향기가 좋습니다. 다른 음식들도 되게 맛있습니다. 2분 덕분에 배터지게 먹었습니다. 감사합니다. ﻿
﻿﻿

stem_filter: 0120﻿ 한 / 中﻿﻿ ﻿﻿ pa.3﻿ ﻿ 이번은 제가 3번째로 촬영에 참여했습니다 . 이번에도 큰 맘 먹어서 나왔습니다 . 욕 많이 먹을 것 같아서 ... 오늘 본 영화는 2004년에 경상남도 밀양시에서 발생한 여중생 집단 성폭행 소건을 바탕으로 만들어진 '한공주'란 작품입니다 . 이 사건은 총 41명의 가해자가 피해자 1명을 거의 1년동안에 100번 넘을 정도로 성폭행을 했습니다 . 이 사건이 밝히고 나서 가해자들도 벌을 제대로 받지 않고 아무렇지 않게 살고 있는데 피해자는 여전히 어렵고 힘들게 지내고 있습니다 . 우리가 이 영화를 통해서 대만과 한국의 미투운동 그리고 여성인권을 토의했습니다.﻿ ﻿ 일단은 이 작품이 사실보다는 이미 더 함축적인 표현과 방식으로 찍었더라도 영화를 봤던 과정에는 제가 무거움과 불편함을 많이 느겼습니다 . 실제 상황을 보면 경찰들이 고문으로 피해자한테 '2차 가해'를 줬습니다 . 피해자가 여성경찰로 중요부위의 상처를 검사해달라고 요구했는데 거부를 받았고 심지어는 남성경찰들이 피해자한테 '니가 저사람들을 꼬신거아냐 ? ' '니가 진짜 밀양시의 치욕이다'고 등등 들어줄 수가 없는 말들을 많이 했습니다 . 한국 지금은 어떻게 하는지 모르겠지만 제가 아는 대만 학생 성폭행 사건으로 얘기하자면 우선 조사할때는 여성경찰로 피해자랑 대화할겁니다 . 그 다음에 사회국 ( 社會局 ) 이라고 하는 국가기관이 사공 ( 社工 , 사화공작사 社會工作師 ) 을 피해자한테 보내줘서 심리적이나 법적인 상담 다 도와줄겁니다 . 혹시나 성폭행의 가해자가 가족이라면 일단 피해자를 다른 데로 옮겨질겁니다 . ﻿ ﻿ 여자주인공이 영화에서 '전 잘못한 게 없는데'라고 얘기했습니다 . 이 한마디로 우리 지금 사는 이 사화가 피해자들을 얼마나 검토하는지 완전하게 털어놓았습니다 . '니가 너무 야하게 입어서 그런거야 ' '니 사생활이 너무 지저분해서 그런거야 ' 이런 비판들 자주 들을 수 있는데 사실은 그렇지 않습니다 . 벨기에 브뤼셀에 '당시에 당신은 무엇을 입었나요 ? ( wear ? ) '라는 전시회가 있었습니다 . 이 전시회의 내용은 성폭행 받었던 피해자들이 사건 발생했을 때는 입었던 옷으로 전시한 것입니다 . 그럼 피해자들 당시에 다 어떤 옷을 입었는가 ? 바로 청바지 , 티셔츠 , 교복 , 유니폼 등등 , 이런 옷들 솔직히 야한 옷도 아닌데 다 아주 흔한 거잖아요 ? 그럼 , 왜 피해자가 반성해야 하는지 이해가 안 됩니다.﻿ ﻿ 여성인권운동과 성평등운동의 발전은 이미 오래되었는데 지금까지는 사람들이 역시 항상 전통적인 생각과 규칙으로 남여성들을 제한을 합니다 . 남자는 그래야 되고 여자는 저래야 되고 여전히 서로서로 상처를 계속 주고 있습니다 . 직장에서도 유리 천장이 많이 남아있습니다 . 얼마전에는 '대만은 세계 성평등 순위 8위를 땄다 ' 이런 기사가 나왔는데 제가 진짜 깜짝 놀랐습니다 . 왜냐하면 대만 같은 상황은 성차별 문제 아직 심각하게 존재하고 있는데 그렇다면 다른 나라들은 상태가 얼마나 안 좋은지는 상상하지도 못 합니다 . 멀지 않은 미래에서 성별과 성적 지향을 막론하고 서로서로 존경을 주고 권력도 평등하게 행사할 수 있으면 좋겠다고 성교육도 제대로 시켜야 더 이상 이런 비극을 없어질 수가 있다고 생각합니다 . 그리고 대만은 어제 혼인평권 ( 婚姻平權 , 동성결혼 ) 초안 이미 나왔습니다 . 먼저 모든 동성애자 커플들한테 축하드립니다 . 꼭 행복하세요 ! ! ﻿ ﻿ 촬영 끝나고 나서 우리가 같이 '금색삼맥'이라는 맥주식당 갔습니다 . 대만사람인데 저도 처음으로 먹으러 갔습니다 . 맥주 전문집이라 맥주 역시 상큼하고 향기가 좋습니다 . 다른 음식들도 되게 맛있습니다 . 2분 덕분에 배터지게 먹었습니다 . 감사합니다 . ﻿ ﻿﻿ pa.3﻿ ﻿ 這次是我第三次參與拍攝，這次也是下了很大的決心才出演的，因為好像會被很多人罵哈哈哈。今天我們所觀賞的電影名為「青春勿語（原文直譯：韓公主）」，是改編自2004年在慶尚南道密陽市所發生的女學生集體性侵事件的作品。在這個事件中，41位的加害人在近乎一年期間對被害人進行了超過100次的性侵行為。在事件爆發之後，加害人們並沒有得到相對的懲罰，反而就像什麼事也沒發生的生活，而被害人則到目前為止都還非常辛苦地活著。我們透過這部電影來探討了台韓的女權及metoo運動。﻿ ﻿ 首先，雖然這部作品已經用了比事實相對隱晦的表現手法來拍攝，但在觀看的過程中我仍然感到非常沉重以及不適。而實際的狀況中，警察們在做筆錄時，給與了被害者不少的「二次加害」。 ( 太長了，留言繼續。너무 길어서 댓글로 할게요 )

'니가 너무 야하게 입어서 그런거야 ' '니 사생활이 너무 지저분해서 그런거야 ' 이런 비판들 자주 들을 수 있는데 사실은 그렇지 않습니다 . 벨기에 브뤼셀에 '당시에 당신은 무엇을 입었나요 ? ( wear ? ) '라는 전시회가 있었습니다 . 이 전시회의 내용은 성폭행 받었던 피해자들이 사건 발생했을 때는 입었던 옷으로 전시한 것입니다 . 그럼 피해자들 당시에 다 어떤 옷을 입었는가 ? 바로 청바지 , 티셔츠 , 교복 , 유니폼 등등 , 이런 옷들 솔직히 야한 옷도 아닌데 다 아주 흔한 거잖아요 ? 그럼 , 왜 피해자가 반성해야 하는지 이해가 안 됩니다.﻿ ﻿ 여성인권운동과 성평등운동의 발전은 이미 오래되었는데 지금까지는 사람들이 역시 항상 전통적인 생각과 규칙으로 남여성들을 제한을 합니다 . 남자는 그래야 되고 여자는 저래야 되고 여전히 서로서로 상처를 계속 주고 있습니다 . 직장에서도 유리 천장이 많이 남아있습니다 . 얼마전에는 '대만은 세계 성평등 순위 8위를 땄다 ' 이런 기사가 나왔는데 제가 진짜 깜짝 놀랐습니다 . 왜냐하면 대만 같은 상황은 성차별 문제 아직 심각하게 존재하고 있는데 그렇다면 다른 나라들은 상태가 얼마나 안 좋은지는 상상하지도 못 합니다 . 멀지 않은 미래에서 성별과 성적 지향을 막론하고 서로서로 존경을 주고 권력도 평등하게 행사할 수 있으면 좋겠다고 성교육도 제대로 시켜야 더 이상 이런 비극을 없어질 수가 있다고 생각합니다 . 그리고 대만은 어제 혼인평권 ( 婚姻平權 , 동성결혼 ) 초안 이미 나왔습니다 . 먼저 모든 동성애자 커플들한테 축하드립니다 . 꼭 행복하세요 ! ! ﻿ ﻿ 촬영 끝나고 나서 우리가 같이 '금색삼맥'이라는 맥주식당 갔습니다 . 대만사람인데 저도 처음으로 먹으러 갔습니다 . 맥주 전문집이라 맥주 역시 상큼하고 향기가 좋습니다 . 다른 음식들도 되게 맛있습니다 . 2분 덕분에 배터지게 먹었습니다 . 감사합니다 . ﻿ ﻿﻿ pa.3﻿ ﻿ 這次是我第三次參與拍攝，這次也是下了很大的決心才出演的，因為好像會被很多人罵哈哈哈。今天我們所觀賞的電影名為「青春勿語（原文直譯：韓公主）」，是改編自2004年在慶尚南道密陽市所發生的女學生集體性侵事件的作品。在這個事件中，41位的加害人在近乎一年期間對被害人進行了超過100次的性侵行為。在事件爆發之後，加害人們並沒有得到相對的懲罰，反而就像什麼事也沒發生的生活，而被害人則到目前為止都還非常辛苦地活著。我們透過這部電影來探討了台韓的女權及metoo運動。﻿ ﻿ 首先，雖然這部作品已經用了比事實相對隱晦的表現手法來拍攝，但在觀看的過程中我仍然感到非常沉重以及不適。而實際的狀況中，警察們在做筆錄時，給與了被害者不少的「二次加害」。 ( 太長了，留言繼續。너무 길어서 댓글로 할게요 )

when the past comes back to haunt youphoto courtesy of noah abrams and udiscovermusic2019 was set to be another big year for ryan adams. the alt-country pioneer has three albums ready to drop with tour dates scheduled throughout the united kingdom and ireland.the tour is primed to offer a window into adams’s world. add-ons include exclusive merchandise and access to ‘ryan’s pinball lair’ and the ‘what am i’ ryan adams gallery, each striving to personalize and commemorate the experience for fans.adams, who’s likened to paul westerberg, big star and gram parsons, is known for his prolific output. when he left whiskeytown, he went solo, releasing 10 albums in as many years, 3 of them (cold roses, jacksonville city nights, and 29) dropping at the same time.in the wake of the new york times piece and an f.b.i. investigation, these back-stage packages seem more like an ironic twist of fate for adams. they’ve become a distorted glimpse into a man whose smiling persona and self-aggrandizing behavior has proven to be nothing short of narcissistic, and as several women allege, predatory.the piece, which was published just over a week ago, details emotionally manipulative and sexually inappropriate behavior between adams and several women. among…

text:
کارل لاگرفلد، طراحی بی نظیر، اما زن ستیز و مهاجر ستیز!
21 فوریه 2019- رها- لایف استایل

19 فوریه  کارل لاگرفلد در سن 85 سالگی فوت کرد. او آلمانی الاصل بود اما با تغییر اسم و محل زندنگی خود، بیشتر عمرش را در فرانسه زندگی کرد. کارل لاگرفلد یکی از طراحان برجسته لباس زنانه بود و بیش از 5 دهه برای مزون های معروف از جمله "شانل" طراحی کرد و با مانکن های معروف این چند دهه همکاری داشت. شوی مدی که وی در سال 2017 در هاوانا برگزار کرد مدتها در صدر تبلیغات دنیای مد و لباس بود.

لاگرفلد که در طراحی لباس بی نظیر بود، فردی به غایت زن ستیزو مهاجر ستیز بود. او تنفر شدیدی به زنانی که سایزهایی بزرگتر از سایز مانکن ها دارند، داشت و آنها را "بی ارزش" می خواند. وی در مصاحبه های متعددی حتی هنرمندان شناخته شده ای که سایز های متوسط دارند را به سخره گرفته بود. او همچنین از دشمنان سرسخت جبش "می تو"  بود . این جنبش طی سال های اخیر علیه سو استفاده های جنسی در دنیای هنر و مد به راه افتاده و بسیای از زنانی که مورد آزار و اذیت جنسی واقع شده اند، سکوت چندین ساله را شکسته اند. لاگرفلد با عباراتی تحقیر کننده و زن ستیزانه در مصاحبه ای  در مورد این جنبش گفته بود "کسانی که نمی خواهند شلوار خود را پائین بکشند، بهتر است وارد این دنیا (مد و هنر) نشوند." علاوه بر این در دوران بحران پناهندگی در سال  2017 و سیاست مرکل در پذیرش مهاجرین، لاگرفلد پرخاش کنان این سیاست را را کوبید و علنا در مصاحبه ای با تلویزیون فرانسه، همه مهاجران را ضد یهودی و خطرناک نامید. 
#karllagerfeld #chenel #misoogyny #fatphobic #fashion #me2 #metoo
#کارل_لاگرفلد #مد #شانل #زن_ستیزی #مهاجرستیزی

sexual assault is not just a criminal justice issue. sexual assault is a public health and human rights issue that profoundly affects victims, their loved ones and society.

common legal issues arising in the aftermath of sexual assault involve safety and family violence concerns, access to health insurance and disability benefits, time off under the family and medical leave, privacy interests, educational effects, and crime victims' compensation claims. many sexual assault survivors are unaware that free legal help is just a phone call away.

speak out today.
#educate #empower #nomore #timesup #metoo #justice #hearmetoo #supportingsurvivors #nomoreapp

text:
she did not consent the kiss. he was drunk, was strong and  grabbed her unwarned. 
chances are you have seen the photograph of george mendonsa kissing greta zimmer friedman on v-j day in 1945. he was a sailor, overwhelmed with the announcement of the end of the war and the fact he did not have to return to the pacific. she, a dental assistant, celebrating the war’s end on her lunch break in times square.
the photograph was published in life magazine and showed mendonsa bending friedman backward as her white uniform rode up her thighs.
george died this week. he wasn’t bad or a rapist, he’s intention was described by him as an spontaneous act of gratitude to the nurses that worked on the battle. friedman, for her part, was caught off guard. “i did not see him approaching, and before i know it i was in this vise grip,” friedman once told an interviewer. “i felt he was very strong, he was just holding me tight . . . it wasn’t really a romantic event,” one day she declared at the library of congress. “it wasn’t my choice to be kissed. the guy just came over and kissed or grabbed.” eventually they became friends but was never lovers. 
the statue vandalism is not our choice of protest but its symbolism is very powerful and should be mentioned. 
if you feel bad about the damaged structure, you should feel worse with violated humans. 
#metoo #feminism #noisno #womensrights #feminist #femme #love #ww2kiss #kissphoto #kiss

i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
вандалы в сарасоте (штат флорида) осквернили статую по мотивам известной фотографии "день победы над японией на таймс-сквер", запечатлевшей поцелуй моряка и медсестры, сообщает риа новости.
неизвестные написали красной краской #metoo (движение против насилия над женщинами) на ноге медсестры. полиция обыскала место происшествия, однако баллончики с краской найти не удалось. никакие другие объекты поблизости не пострадали от вандалов.
⠀
предположительно, инцидент произошел в понедельник, 18 февраля, во второй половине дня, однако точное время установить невозможно, так как на месте происшествия не установлены камеры наблюдения. также полиции не удалось найти свидетелей.
⠀
ущерб, нанесенный статуе, оценивается в размере более 1 тысячи долларов.
⠀
14 августа 1945 года, когда япония приняла условия капитуляции, жители нью-йорка вышли на улицы. в тот момент моряк джордж мендоса заметил 21-летнюю фридман – ассистентку дантиста в халате медсестры - и спонтанно поцеловал ее.
⠀
трогательный момент запечатлел фотожурналист альфред эйзенштадт. фото получило название "день победы над японией на таймс-сквер", однако по всему миру оно больше известно как просто "поцелуй". впервые оно было напечатано в журнале life.

stop_filter_tweet: вандалы в сарасоте ( штат флорида ) осквернили статую по мотивам известной фотографии `` день победы над японией на таймс-сквер '' , запечатлевшей поцелуй моряка и медсестры , сообщает риа новости . неизвестные написали красной краской ( движение против насилия над женщинами ) на ноге медсестры . полиция обыскала место происшествия , однако баллончики с краской найти не удалось . никакие другие объекты поблизости не пострадали от вандалов . ⠀ предположительно , инцидент произошел в понедельник , 18 февраля , во второй половине дня , однако точное время установить невозможно , так как на месте происшествия не установлены камеры наблюдения . также полиции не удалось найти свидетелей . ⠀ ущерб , нанесенный статуе , оценивается в размере более 1 тысячи долларов . ⠀ 14 августа 1945 года , когда япония приняла условия капитуляции , жители нью-йорка вышли на улицы . в тот момент моряк джордж мендоса заметил 21-летнюю фридман – ассистентку дантиста в халате медсестры - и спонтанно поцеловал ее . ⠀ трогательный момент запечатлел фотожурналист альфред эйзенштадт . фото получило название `` день победы над японией на таймс-сквер '' , однако по всему миру оно больше известно как просто `` поцелуй '' . впервые оно было напечатано в журнале life .

text:
i wept myself to sleep
as i let go off the part 
of me that you said will
make me less of a woman
-my voice. 
years later, i realise that
this voice, is the only 
force that wouldn’t 
cripple my confidence 
just like you did. 
this voice, is a battle
between the parts of me
that have been subdued
and the parts that want 
to break free. 
this voice is the essence
of being a woman. .
.
.
.
.

text:
whenever i crossed 
the gutters i feel into
.
.
.
◾it! the power of the mind has never thought more than my consistent embarrassment!
◾you wouldn't believe if i told you!
.
◾whenever i cross any gutter i see myself fall into it before i fall into it in real time
.
◾this time, as i walked carefully along the rough paths of my university walkways
.
◾i saw this huge gutter, and i saw a picture in my head before me, falling into that particular gutter!
.
◾so, in other to be careful and avoid that from happening, i meticulously remember stretching my legs over to a pavement just to cross over
.
◾the next thing i remember, i was in a sharp pain, i saw bruises, people were helping me out of the gutter (luckily there was no dirty water)
.
◾all attention was on the girl who just feel into the gutter, all i heard was "eiyaa sorry o" "chai, you should have been more careful" "why were you not looking, kwaun?"
.
◾if only they new, that got me thinking how creepily powerful the thoughts we have in our minds are everyday!
.
◾this got me thinking how powerful the pictures we let form into our minds everyday!
.
◾after this happened for like 3 more times! i manned up! (imagine!!)
.
◾before any pictures appear in my head, (you must watch it) because i have so much authority to uphold or cast it all out!
.
◾afterall, i am in charge here
.
◾it had never happened since this conscious decision! 👇👇👇👇👇let me know what you think!
.
are you in charge?
.
.
#sunshineoluoha #motivation #documentinglife #metoo #more #lady #60secclub #life #strategy

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
after running a #metoo blog for the legal profession last year and receiving hundreds of emails from people who had been sexually harassed, i applied to the nz law foundation for funding to build a reporting platform which would enable people to come forward as a group. i think there is a huge need for this because most reporting systems are designed for people to report on their own - which is very daunting. low reporting rates mean that perpetrators usually go on to sexually harass multiple people and the same can be said for perpetrators of bullying.

to cut a long story short, i made a lot of noise about this on linkedin and was contacted by two very tool tech entrepreneurs, neta meidav and rotem hayoun-meidav, who had just set up a reporting platform called vault platform. this platform enables group reporting of any type of misconduct and has a whole lot of other amazing features, as outlined in the bbc article (link in bio). i am so stoked to partner up with neta and rotem to bring vault platform to nz and australia. if you're a proactive employer and keen to learn more about vault platform i'll be speaking at legal personnel in auckland on 7 march from 4-6pm. to register email sonia.waring@legalpersonnel.co.nz 
it would be great to see you there!

text:
с детства мама всегда учила быть на стрёме.
аккуратно рассказывая истории о насилии и не нормальных людях.
«не вздумай садиться в машину к незнакомому»
«не пей с незнакомыми, вдруг что-то подсыпят ты даже не увидишь»
«будь аккуратна, позвони мне когда приедешь домой»
«не ходи одна поздно вечером»
и всё в этом роде, каждой девочке это знакомо.
я не понимала, почему мама так переживает.
⠀
к чему это я. утром прочитала пост @alexandramitroshina 
кто не в курсе, тема была об изнасиловании девушки.
⠀
становится страшно. 
страшно что столько идиотов, которые могут воспользоваться чей-то наивностью, глупостью, беззащитностью. и остаться безнаказанным.
«сама виновата, надо было думать».
⠀
вот скажите, а вы в каждом своём новом знакомстве видите особого преступника ?
нет
симпатичный молодой человек может вам понравится.
непринуждённое  общение, флирт. это совсем не повод без согласия и с напором домогаться девушку.
⠀
насилие сейчас показывают везде.
это кажется видимо нормой.
это не есть норма, если ломается психика.
⠀
таких случаев много. они бывают не только от алкогольного опьянения, если вам вдруг вздумалось ещё раз обвинить мысленно жертву происшествия. .
тема поднимается не для того чтобы защищать  и наводить ужас вокруг.
а для того чтобы включали головы и выключали «животные инстинкты».
близость должна быть по обоюдному согласию и желанию.

воспитывайте своих детей в любви и с правильными моральными принципами 🙏🏼.
.
#мысливслух #metoo #феминизм

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
find a man that:
a) takes you plant shopping, kindly reminds you that you have too many plants (but silently watches you put two more in his car anyway).
b) goes cookbook shopping, joins you in judging all of them while having great conversation about mario batali and john besh (#metoo).
c) is excited to play your games (and sometimes, you let them win).
d) and stalks your gram without adding you as a friend, and wonders why you haven’t followed him (i don’t follow people first...you should know that buddy).
#foodplantsbooks

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
when i look at this little i girl, i think back to how she always worried about the past, present, and future. i think about how bubbly, happy, and a little shy she was in front of those she didn’t know. she always had that pokerface when it counted the most although she was constantly hurting inside. you see, this little girl had already been through hell and back before being old enough to buy a drink at the bar. the weight of the world was on her shoulders. despite all she had been through, everyone around her was constantly doubting her strength, her beauty, her intelligence, her intellect, and most of all, her well being. many many things she’s been through could have held her down from moving forward with life but it didn’t because she’s strong as fuck!

the past couple of months have made me question the woman i have become and what i have been through. it took one picture to remind myself everything i always knew of myself then and still, today. i deserve what’s best for me, always. there has never been a moment in my life where i didn’t overcome my obstacles and put up a fight. again and again, i have proven everyone in my life wrong because i know that i believe in me, i trust in me, and that i am the force to be reckoned with. i am so proud of where i am and who i have become. i’ve already been through the trenches and i continue to survive. nothing will stop me from continuously moving forward. #metoo #16yome

the past couple of months have made me question the woman i have become and what i have been through. it took one picture to remind myself everything i always knew of myself then and still, today. i deserve what’s best for me, always. there has never been a moment in my life where i didn’t overcome my obstacles and put up a fight. again and again, i have proven everyone in my life wrong because i know that i believe in me, i trust in me, and that i am the force to be reckoned with. i am so proud of where i am and who i have become. i’ve already been through the trenches and i continue to survive. nothing will stop me from continuously moving forward. #metoo #16yome

text:
in 2015, i met a guy through airbnb while travelling in mexico city. over drinks, he told me his deepest secret which not even his family or best friend knew. both our lives changed forever as i filmed him for the next 3 years to tell his story. and we hope that the world is finally ready to listen.

en 2015, conocí a un chico a través de airbnb mientras viajaba por la ciudad de méxico. mientras tomábamos unas copas, me contó su secreto más profundo que ni siquiera su familia o su mejor amigo conocían. ambas vidas cambiaron para siempre cuando lo filmé durante los siguientes 3 años para contar su historia. y esperamos que el mundo esté finalmente listo para escuchar.

hear us | escúchanos: www.change.org/p/support-male-survivors-of-sexual-assault

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: safety work hits upon a few themes that we felt were important to tell through this story. one being the theme of “safety work”, as the name suggests. safety work is defined as any conscious or unconscious action taken by women to try and protect themselves and avoid sexual harassment or violence. this includes taking particular routes when walking, or not walking at night, looking under your car before you approach it and get in, watching your drink as it’s being poured and not setting it down, or carrying pepper spray just to get back to your car in the dark. our film safety work follows lead, lily, as she tries to make it back to her motel room after a day of auditions all while trying to navigate making choices that ensure her safety, in more ways than one. i don’t want to give away too much, but can’t wait for you all to see the whole story! have you ever heard of the term safety work before? what do you think of it? link in bio to an article with a little more on safety work (https://qz.com/1433494/all-the-things-women-do-to-avoid-sexual-harassment/)

call for participants! 
i am looking for womxn, or those who identify as womxn, to participate in my ongoing photographic social practice work, the panty project. womxn like myself who have been affected by various forms of abuse, whether physical or emotional, and whether cultural or interpersonal. all of our stories are important. i am inviting all womxn to share stories with me, and ultimately, with each other so we can empower, console, and inspire. 
contact: b@babetteshaw.art
.

tweet_full:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said.
.
- the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
hi, my name is roxanne darling (@roxannedarling) and this is my week to takeover instagram from the los angeles center of photography (lacp) @la_centerofphoto. i am an emerging artist currently living in santa fe, nm. i love that lacp welcomes out-of-state photographers to be part of their community. this week, let's talk about bodies, nature, and getting older!

image: 
i am: rocking my rebirth in quartzite

the photos i’m sharing this week are of me, from my series of portraits in nature. as a 66-year-old woman and emerging artist, i’m exploring the:
* the natural desire to be unclothed outdoors, in the privacy of precious places;
* a newly discovered quality of self-acceptance for my aging self;
* an appetite to create art from the female gaze, as a type of reclaiming my time, my body, and my point of view.

the photos were taken in 2017-2018 on an extended rv trip around the western us with my partner. in many cases, the place itself spoke up first and invited me to explore ways of finding myself in nature. as a card-carrying member of the #metoo movement, i hope this work conveys a type of freedom of self-expression that is possible regardless of one’s painful past experiences.

the photos were shot using several cameras: iphone, dji drone, and a canon dslr. all images have been cropped square; some images have been slightly modified to meet instagram rules. *
*
*

text:
“they say you’re just here for fun, until you find a husband”

cesca menyadari bahwa kebanyakan perempuan pekerja di indonesia harus menghadapi beberapa hal kurang menyenangkan yang tidak selalu dihadapi pekerja laki-laki. ada sebuah stigma yang cukup populer, dimana perempuan akan mengesampingkan karirnya ketika mulai berumah-tangga. stigma ini tentu tidak pernah melekat kepada laki-laki. “whenever i interviewed in indonesia, a lot of people asked about my relationship status, whether i plan to have kids, and off course it annoys me because you’re not asking men these questions”

karena demikian, sejak mulai bekerja perempuan seringkali mendapat tekanan untuk membuktikan keseriusannya dalam karir. disinilah keadaan menjadi semakin sulit. misalnya, ketika ada ajakan makan malam bersama tim kerja, perempuan yang menolak akan dianggap tidak cocok dengan dinamika dunia profesional. “are you the type of girl who can’t handle working late?”
.
"the problem is, our behavior are always being criticized.” hal yang dianggapnya janggal dalam isu pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja yang rentan menghantui perempuan pekerja adalah bagaimana posisi perempuan dan segala tidak tanduknya selalu dipertanyakan. ketika perempuan merasa tidak nyaman atas perlakuan tertentu, tidak mudah untuk mengutarakannya. “if you complain about sexual harassment, you are labeled as hysterical, attention seeking, troublesome”. cesca bahkan mempunyai pengalaman ketika ia berbicara terhadap kelakuan atasan yang kurang pantas, lagi-lagi yang dipertanyakan adalah pakaian yang ia kenakan dan apakah ia memicu kejadian tersebut.

•
kalau gk konsen bisa jadi kamu melecehkan orang lain loh. •
tapi sayang banget sampai saat ini masih banyak yang belum paham kalau “diam” itu bukan konsen, kalau “terpaksa” itu bukan konsen, kalau saya mau dipegang tangannya belum tentu saya mau dicium, kalau saya mau dicium belum tentu saya mau dipeluk, kalau saya mau dipeluk belum tentu saya mau diajak berhubungan seks!
•
pahami yah teman-teman! •
terus dari mana kita bisa mendapatkan kesepakatan / konsensual? bertanyalah! simple kan! jangan memperlakukan tubuh orang lain hanya berdasarkan asumsimu tanpa bertanya pada yang punya tubuh.

text:
#tanyakenapa #sekadarmengingatkan
sering nggak sih dengar kalimat ini?
“kalau nggak mau dilecehin, jangan pakai baju seksi dong. salah sendiri!”
kita tentu sering mendengar kalimat tersebut ketika orang lain justru malah membenarkan tindak pelecehan terhadap perempuan.
logika tersebut sangat keliru, karena bentuk tubuh dan cara berpakaian korban tidak dapat menjadi pembenaran bagi seseorang untuk melalukan tindak pelecehan seksual. tidak pula dapat dijadikan legitimasi bagi negara untuk mengeluarkan kebijakan yang mengatur ekspresi termasuk cara berpakaian perempuan.
dunia patriarki menghendaki perempuan menjadi manusia lemah lembut, penurut, tidak tegas dan bergantung pada orang lain. mayoritas perempuan tumbuh dalam situasi tersebut, sehingga keberanian dan ketegasan dalam melawan pelecehan seksual menjadi tidak mudah untuk dilakukan.
memberi contoh keberanian untuk melawan tindak pelecehan tentu akan memberikan suatu gambaran berbeda dari konstruksi sosial yang sudah mapan. menunjukkan bahwa perempun tidak lemah & mampu melawan, akan menginspirasi perempuan lain untuk juga berani melawan pelecehan seksual.@jaringanmuda

text:
tak seorangpun menghendaki perkosaan, tak ada sesuatu apapun yang dapat disebut mengundang perkosaan. perkosaan adalah kejahatan kemanusiaan karena merendahkan orang lain secara sepihak sebagai objek seksual belaka, merampas harga diri orang lain secara sepihak dan sewenang-wenang demi kepuasan seksual.
•
cara pandang yang masih sering menyalahkan korban justru membuat pembatasan ruang gerak tidak ditujukan pada pelaku melainkan pada korban seperti contoh: adanya jam malam bagi perempuan, aturan berpakaian, cara berperilaku, bertutur serta berbagai ekspresi lainnya.
•
hingga saat ini belum ada peringatan & tindakan tegas bagi pelaku, sehingga berdampak pada pembiaran kasus kekerasan seksual yang membuat korban semakin diam dan malu untuk melaporkan. •
•
dengan disahkannya ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksual, tak hanya akan menjerat pelaku, tapi juga memberikan landasan hukum yang kuat untuk mencegah timbulnya korban.
•
@dpr_ri jangan lamban, jangan biarkan korban semakin bertambah. segera sahkan ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksual!!! kami butuh jaminan rasa aman dan bebas dari kekerasan seksual @jaringanmuda
—————————————————————-

text:
congratulations for 6 months on the dr. kate truitt & associates team to our very own dr. megan mansfield! i was lucky to meet dr. mansfield back in 2016 when she asked me to participate in her dissertation which ultimately became a powerful guide for psychotherapists who treat lesbian sexual assault survivors. dr. mansfield’s insight, wisdom, and clinical capacity is such a gift to both her patients and our team. not only a healer, she’s an innovator and has been designing new opportunities for incorporating psychosensory work into trauma  interventions in group settings that are already seeing unparalleled results in patient healing and recovery. we are beyond delighted to have this inspiring woman on our team and i am honored to be a part of her professional journey.

text:
exageración
al salir del establecimiento descubrió que la luz del sol era inexistente y que unas amarillentas lámparas intentaban remplazar su fulgor. miró hacia todos lados, no había nadie a la vista. tenía que caminar alrededor de diez cuadras para llegar a la parada de colectivos. 
con cada paso una pesada incomodidad crecía, algunos la llamaban miedo, otros inseguridad y muchos exageración. sus piernas andaban cada vez más rápido, sus ojos revoloteaban hacia todos lados buscando algo sospechoso, algún indicio de peligro. sus latidos se precipitaban y sus manos sudaban.
caminaba solo por senderos iluminados, aunque no podía evitar los que no lo estaban. pensaba en todo lo que valía la pena en su vida, en todo lo que podría perder si se encontraba con una persona equivocada. 
de repente, su sangre se heló al ver en un rincón de la vereda a un individuo. se refugiaba entre sombras y ella recordó la vez en la que un sujeto comenzó a seguirla en esa misma calle. 
se cambió de vereda y aceleró sus pasos. unas débiles lágrimas habían comenzado a caer por sus mejillas, tenía miedo e impotencia.
por su mente pululaban los incontables secuestros, violaciones y muertes de mujeres como ella. temía formar parte de esa lista. sabía que si algo así le ocurría la importancia del crimen sería relegada a la vestimenta que llevaba ese día o la incógnita de por qué estaba sola. muchos dirían que se lo buscó por andar sola de noche y automáticamente la culpa sería solo de ella.
sus lagrimas se convirtieron en un llanto inconsolable. no soportaba la injusticia, le generaba una inmensa frustración, pero sabía que si se quejaba, la llamarían exagerada o le dirían que se lo buscó. ella siempre tendría la culpa.
sin darse cuenta llegó a la parada y vio al colectivo acercándose. sonrió con los ojos ahogados, con el corazón acelerado, con la respiración agitada. había sobrevivido una noche más a la "exageración". #feminismo #niunamenos #violenciadegenero #abortolegal #machismo #abortolegalya #patriarcado #mujeres #girlpower #miracomonosponemos #feminazi #woman #sevaacaer #esi #igualdad #empoderamiento #metoo #abajoelpatriarcado #feminisart #vivasnosqueremos

text:
there once was a story of a man that discovered a beautiful creature trying to escape its cocoon. the man watched as the creature struggled and writhed trying to break free. he watched as the head and the neck emerged...but after hours of this, he couldn’t bear to watch it suffer any longer. he took out his knife and cut the creature free. but the creature was not fully formed and it’s legs were weak. it’s wings were brittle and could not carry its body. it only lived a short while on its feeble legs and died soon after. 
sometimes we ask why we go through hard times. we blame god, others, circumstances...for every tough trial we go through. yet we fail to see that only through fire can gold be formed. you are gold. you are a diamond. you may not be able to see the future but you can become strong. resilient. you can choose to allow the fire to make your soul beautiful.
