text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
change coming to @thewordforthis 🖤✒ •
the thinking and intuitive parts of my brain have been at war, and i need to let intuition lead thinky von wordybrain for a bit. i’ve been accused of being unable to do anything half-assed (insert “whole ass”-and-its-reverse joke here). overachieving has always been my hypervigilant survival baseline, and while it’s a detrimental trait detrimental, i’m struggling to let go of it. •
i had a conversation with a work mentor/aunt/older-sister this evening, a woman i trust and feel personally/professionally safe with. she knows about #fibromyalgia / #chronicillness crap, and is worried about me, and with reason. we haven’t gotten into the specifics of why this work is healing and necessary for me, but she urged me to think about whether it’s taking a toll. it is, but not in the way she thought. my volunteer work with @rainn is just getting started, and it’s feeding me far more than it’s depleting me. that’s hard for a lot of people to understand. •
but: there’s a simple change that'll greatly reduce the pressure i’ve created to meet my own expectations. so, a small adjustment in how i’m structuring this account: maintaining the visual aesthetic requires six posts a week… or, it could be three. the “share your story” part of this platform will always exist. i stopped seeking it as actively for other reasons, and so submissions are fewer and further between. doing those more occasionally, perhaps sharing a few at a time here since they’re always posted individually on my website, will give me the flexibility to keep the overall aesthetic – with less pressure to create content when i’m so exhausted i can barely move. that was never supposed to be the point. •
so, that’s my self-care compromise. i’ll still be active in engaging with you and with others, but as an example of how it’ll work, my next post will be sunday, when we do #twft52 prompt 8. i’m going to take it week by week. i’m in it with you, and i always will be. thanks for being in it with *me*. original image via @pexels. [image: b&w high-angle view of waves crashing against mountain beaches. text: "intuition will tell the thinking mind where to look next. -jonas salk"]

text:
on tuesday night, more than a dozen protesters, including representatives from black lives matter and the #metoo movement, stood outside the west hollywood library and called for the resignation of embattled mayor john duran. duran has been a target of ire for weeks now—and not just for allegedly groping fellow members of the gay men’s chorus or sexually harassing a former employee.⁣
__________⁣
“i am appalled by the behavior and language the mayor of west hollywood has used over the last week to describe and excuse his actions,” said estevan montemayor, former chair of the west hollywood public safety commission. “he has excused his behavior because of the gay liberation movement, which is an insult to the gay liberation movement.”⁣
__________⁣

text:
i didn’t reach the peak of this mountain. instead of leaving for the trek on time that morning, i abruptly checked out of my hotel two days early and found a new place to stay—because i could no longer ignore or sidestep the harassment of my hotel’s host/manager.

a few days earlier he had tried (quite uninvited) to come onto me, in my room, late at night. and despite promises after that to keep his distance—which is why i didn’t immediately leave—he regularly texted or showed up at my door unnecessarily. the creep wanted me to make him feel better about his bad behaviour. he wanted me to reassure him that everything was ok, say we were friends and could hang out, which i refused to do. but since i also wanted to continue my stay at the hotel (i’d prepaid and it was a beautiful space), i tried to be civil. a male friend asked me why i didn’t just tell him to screw off, hit him etc. and i attempted to explain what most women know intuitively. that we temper our words and actions to protect our safety. because when there is a threat and we are vulnerable, the best option is often appeasement or retreat. i cannot describe how much this pisses me off, but it’s reality.

many people ask why i travel solo when i regularly experience harassment in some places. my answer is: because i fucking want to travel on my own. and hella brave women before me fought for that to be an option. they fought for women to take up space and explore and have a voice. so i’ll keep doing what i’m doing (and a lot of other women i know are doing the same), hopefully chipping away, place by place, at the systems and norms that allow or encourage harassment and assault. 
p.s. enjoy my scathing review on every platform possible dickhead🖕🏼
.
.
.
.
.

text:
**trigger warning** sexual assault** this week, for the 1st time in a while, somebody had the courage to share with me their experience of sexual assault. 
i was a little caught off guard, but appreciated their courage. 
they said "i know exactly how you feel, you just put the pain into a box, and put another box around it and another and another"
whilst i did used to run away from the pain and trauma, the constant unexpected triggers made life exhausting. i lost a lot of years to hiding from the past and avoiding the hurt. 
it was only when i decided to stop hiding and empty all those boxes that i started to live again, rather than just surviving. 
this isn't just about survivors of sexual assault. this is for anybody who has pain in boxes. believe me, facing the trauma is hard, but it's a lot harder to carry a load you weren't made to bear 💗

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

..
despite your circumstances, what are you grateful for?

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
smollett is officially a suspect for filing a false police report.  the issue with all fale crimes is that it takes credibility away from actual crimes. when a woman falsely accuses a man of sexual assault, that makes other sexual assault cases easily put off or lost.  same with hate crimes.  now all hate crimes come into question.  he's not doing anyone any favors, but instead just made democratic front runners for president look like fools (they are, but hes not helping his party). and to the people upset that this was fake, why would we want america to be painted as a racist horrible place to live? we all know its not, thats why theres thousands of caravans of people trying to get here illegally. 
he needs to serve time.  the actual crimes in chicago were put off to help this doomphus.  1 in 6 murders in chicago go unsolved. this is a primarily black area. how is he helping "his people"? imagine being one of those families, knowing that this crime was fake and your loved ones killer is out there still. horrible. hope he pays.
another thing to add, what about the jewish man who was attacked by three men, nothing stolen? why was this not reported? 🇺🇸
#politics #political #america #chicago #newyork #jussiesmollett #fakenews #hoax #metoo #jews #republican #democract #conservative #libertarian #libtard #liberal

another thing to add, what about the jewish man who was attacked by three men, nothing stolen? why was this not reported? 🇺🇸

text:
so....in advance please please take your own emotional well being into mind before watching this tedtalk. it has triggering aspects that might cause some very painful emotions to surface.
•
i listen to the tedtalk hour on spotify’s podcast and it was labeled forgiveness so i put it on while doing other stuff. hearing thordis elva and tom strange’s story was heartbreaking and really triggered a lot of emotions for myself from my own rape because it was such a different way to confront sexual violence.
•
in this day and age of #metoo i find positives and negatives of the movement. due to the limelight you will unfortunately get people who lie. this in no way discredits those who have gone through actual events.
•
it’s always so hard for me to talk about this because it’s looked upon so badly in the american society specially for the victim. like we should hide what happened, get over it (like many people have told me), and be ashamed of ourselves like we are the ones to blame for what has happened!
•
i want there to be places that help women/men who have dealt with sexual violence that aren’t almost impossible to find or when you do find a place charges you so much for help that you end up leaving.
•
i was in that situation wanting to commit suicide and i had planned it out. i couldn’t afford help after i found a clinic. it was like the final blow and honestly i tried drinking myself to death for a time longer than i would like to admit.
•
i bring this up because i really look up to the @thordiselva and how strong and determined she was to find her own happiness in life through reconciliation. i really related to how she felt before writing her letter to tom stranger and it gave me hope that maybe one day i would be completely free of these feelings and memories i was forcibly given. thank you for sharing and giving me this hope @thordiselva 💜
youtube link:
https://youtu.be/gypoqfcvt9w
.
.
#hope #metoo #womenempowerment #survivor #strongwomen #wcw #lettinggo #peaceofmind #loveyourself #forgiveness #happinessfromwithin

text:
self talk ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
this is who i am 80% of the day ⁣(alan watts in the background)
⁣⁣
talking to myself - i keep it quiet when i’m around people but i talk to myself out loud all day ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i am constantly working on my positive/reflective self talk ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i’m trying to find myself but i know i never will⁣⁣
⁣⁣
it will be the journey of my life to know what i am capable of - to know what i can accomplish ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i don’t give a fuck about money-fame -big houses or vacations ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i care about expanding myself to the point of exhaustion ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i hope i die from it ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i’m not telling you to live this life - most don’t want a reflective life- it’s too painful for most but i am happy doing it ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i’ve actually never been happier⁣⁣
⁣⁣
what i am asking you to do is listen to that voice that i let out in this video to come out once in a while - in the shower at home - in the car- have conversations with yourself ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
talk to yoursef- love yourself - be kind to yourself ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
but at the same time when that voice is nagging you to do something you’ve been afraid of for years - fucking do it! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i love myself enough to be the best version of myself possible - i hope you do too ❤️⁣
⁣
255# ⁣

#limitless #itsnotheproblemitshowyoureact #sefllove #selfcare #cbd #heavylifting #snatch #fitness #loveyourself #endocannabinoid #endocannabinoiddeficiency #borderlinepersonalitydisorder #endocannabinoidsystem #mentalhealth #mensmentalhealth #womensmentalhealth #talktomenice #timetotalk #timetoreflect

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
rape is a particularly difficult crime because it's about both power and violence. rapists use sex organs as the locus of their violence, but rape isn't about sex, at least not in the sense of being motivated by sexual attraction or an uncontrollable sexual urge. rapists don't rape because they can't get sex elsewhere. rapists don't rape because they're uncontrollably turned on by the sight of some cleavage, or a midriff, or lipstick, or an ankle. they rape because they're misogynist sadists, and they flourish in places where misogyny is justified as tradition and maleness comes with a presumption of violence.
i am tired of being asked the wrong questions. i am tired of being blamed for being a victim of a violent crime. attempts to silence survivors are working less and less, as we are getting tired. we are fighting back.

comment below: what victim blaming questions/comments have you been asked? or comment a 💖 below to show support for survivors.

تجتمع مع الممثل oh dal soo بعد فضيحة حملة metoo،لكنها تنفي عودته إلى الترفيه
_
في 20 فبراير، أكدت c-jes entertainment تقارير سابقة ذكرت أن ممثلي الوكالة عقدوا مؤخرًا اجتماعًا مع الممثل oh dal soo.

يتوقّف الممثل حاليًا عن التمثيل بعد اتهامه بالتحرش الجنسي من خلال حملة “#metoo” ، في مطلع العام الماضي، وقالت سي-جي لوسائل الإعلام: “نظرًا لحقيقة أن الممثل لا يمتلك حاليًا وكالة، فقد عقدنا اجتماعًا لمناقشة بعض اعماله التي تأخرت عن العرض الأول، بالإضافة إلى المشكلات الأخرى التي لم تحل، ومع ذلك، لا يشير ذلك بالضرورة إلى عودته إلى عالم الترفيه”

في الوقت الحالي، هناك ثلاثة أفلام مكتملة تشمل “control” و “i want to meet your parents in person” و “neighbour” يتم تعليقها من العرض الأول في السينما بسبب حادثة oh dal soo المثيرة للجدل.
.
.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
hi, my name is roxanne darling (@roxannedarling) and this is my week to takeover instagram from the los angeles center of photography (lacp) @la_centerofphoto. i am an emerging artist currently living in santa fe, nm. i love that lacp welcomes out-of-state photographers to be part of their community. this week, let's talk about bodies, nature, and getting older!

image: 
i am: channeling auntie georgia in abiquiu

the photos i’m sharing this week are of me, from my series of portraits in nature. as a 66-year-old woman and emerging artist, i’m exploring the:
* the natural desire to be unclothed outdoors, in the privacy of precious places;
* a newly discovered quality of self-acceptance for my aging self;
* an appetite to create art from the female gaze, as a type of reclaiming my time, my body, and my point of view.

the photos were taken in 2017-2018 on an extended rv trip around the western us with my partner. in many cases, the place itself spoke up first and invited me to explore ways of finding myself in nature. as a card-carrying member of the #metoo movement, i hope this work conveys a type of freedom of self-expression that is possible regardless of one’s painful past experiences.

the photos were shot using several cameras: iphone, dji drone, and a canon dslr. all images have been cropped square; some images have been slightly modified to meet instagram rules. *
*
*

text:
clarence thomas calls for reconsidering libel standards as supreme court rejects cosby case

thomas signals he'd reject the "actual malice" standard established in a landmark 1964 opinion. but it won't be in a case that presented the issue of whether an individual becomes a public figure by simply making an accusation of being victimized.

the u.s. supreme court has passed on an opportunity to examine speech in the #metoo era. on tuesday, the justices on the high court declined review of a case brought by bill cosby accuser kathrine mckee, who alleged being defamed when cosby’s attorney characterized her story of being raped four decades ago as a fabricated lie. while the high court won't tackle mckee's case, today's order is most notable because of a concurring statement from justice clarence thomas who is calling for a re-examination of the jurisprudence that has made it more tough for public figures to carry defamation claims in court.

the denial of certiorari in kathrine mckee v. william cosbycomes five months after the comedian was sentenced to three to 10 years in prison for sexually assaulting another woman andrea constand. before finally weighing in on mckee's case, the justices deferred consideration nearly a dozen times over the course of several months perhaps out of sensitivity surrounding the capitol hill confirmation fight over brett kavanaugh, who himself was accused of sexual misconduct.

text:
becoming a parent in #activeaddiction is still so negatively stigmatized, even by other addicts (in and out of recovery). the comments on videos of moms using are heartbreaking but i know slowly the views are shifting.  hundreds of people reacted in support on my #lovewhatmatters story giving me a new sense of responsibility to share my story and raise awareness of #addiction and #motherhood.
.
 addiction is not cured with children. the pain i see consume women who believed with every ounce of themselves that they would never relapse in motherhood is devastating. the #shame that washes over you when you seemingly "choose" drugs over your kids is dark and will drown you if you don't get help. #youareloved #yourchildrenneedyou .
my children love me unconditionally and deserve a healthy mom. whatever resources i used to make that happen were worth it. .
me pregnant with my oldest in 2011 vs. now. 8 years ago. i was dying in silence. .
#mominrecovery #12steps #blessed #5yearssober #recoveryblog #sobernation #sobermom #motherhoodinrecovery #postpartumdepression #metoo #endthestigma #addiction #useyourvoice

text:
a real conversation about toxic masculinity, sexual abuse and trauma, relationships on the @themajichour and that’s only part 1!

we just dropped episode #18: how to be a “man”, with visionary thought leader sara gustafson. replacing “toxic masculinity” with balance.
☯️
men, we’re on your side! on this episode we explore what our guest, sara gustafson, describes as: “the death of the american male”, including what “toxic masculinity” is and how we as society have woven it into our culture and relationships, including in the bedroom!
💟
as a visionary thought leader, authenticity expert, and truth seeking provocateur, sara sparks healing and transformation through her powerful life coaching and holistic wellness programs. she is a champion for radical self-care who has embraced the empowered divine feminine within, while giving credit where credit is due to the much needed masculine energies and both the men and women who embody them.
☯️
as this episode progresses we sort through some of the controversy surrounding “feminism” and the #metoo movement, disrupting what you might think you know about these subjects. as much as these topics might feel skewed toward females in our current culture, sara gives us an unbiased look at how important it is for both men and women to focus on working together to find a balance.
💟 @womenwhoraisehell @thejadebryce 
head on over to the link in our bio to listen. 🔮✨💋

text:
a couple of weeks ago, as i was preparing to give a lecture on secondary trauma and the #metoo movement, i realized that i, too, had suffered post-traumatic syndrome last year without realizing it. 😞

for at least nine months, as i was buried in my apartment studying for grad school, i was mostly disconnected from myself. ☹️ why so much violence against women everywhere on the globe, why the painful troubled relationships, why the self-abandonment, why the low self-esteem, why the disempowerment, why the self-destructiveness being promoted as feminism...how it all started - that was all i could think about. 🤦🏾‍♀️ i couldn't talk.
i couldn't write.
i couldn't see clients.

i needed to contextualize the unfortunate never ending need for my work.
i needed to out together the puzzle in my head.

and although i was exposing myself to very traumatic material all day every day, i couldn't exit. 
i was just in a dark hole.🤯 i've been climbing out of it and doing all the things i know and teach (the irony!) since june. many of them, some of you generously shared with me that you practice attending to your emotional needs. (thank you!) i've been able to navigate myself to a healthy place.☺️ still grieving. 
still heart-broken.
and way more awaken to our wild and precious condition as humans on this beautiful planet.

when i was in that prolonged darkness, however, i couldn't meditate, or do yoga, or journal. what really helped me was the emotional support i received — the connection with other human beings. the nourishment in the listening, in the understanding, in the validating, in the hugs, in the shoulders for me to cry on. 
loves, so many are carrying so much without enough nourishment coming in. what kind of emotional support do you have? who are the people whose presence regulates your nervous system? 
we are immersed in a world of suffering, and there's a sense of increased vulnerability. let us not forget: we hurt each other, but we also heal each other.

today on #grottonetwork.com, a clinical social worker is sharing how to best help a friend who survived sexual assault. you don’t need to be their therapist or lawyer — you just need to be their friend.

let's show up with care, thoughtfulness, empathy, and compassion for our friends who have experienced sexual assault.

read the full story via the link in our bio.

vorrei sfruttare l'occasione per dire due cosine, in particolar modo alle donne. vorrei dirvi di non credere mai di non essere all'altezza di qualcosa o di qualcuno, di non pensare di meritare di soffrire nonostante possiate essere coscienti di aver commesso degli errori nella vostra vita.. di non smettere di credere in futuro a causa di qualcosa o qualcuno, di non smettere di credere nell'amore perché vi è stata tolta la speranza e soprattutto di non credere mai che l'amore sia legato alla sofferenza.. vorrei consigliarvi di parlare con qualcuno quando c'è qualcosa che non vi fa stare bene, di rivolgersi a persone competenti se la situazione è anche ai vostri occhi più grave. vorrei consigliarvi di amarvi da sole, ogni giorno, ogni minuto così da poter essere felici sempre e magari di incontrare qualcuno che vi ami ulteriormente e che meriti il vostro amore ❤

text:
i want to take a second to talk about something that’s been on my mind since karl lagerfeld’s passing yesterday. i’ve looked up to him for as long as i can remember, so when @rosierosedesigner posted about karl’s disparaging comments towards the #metoo movement, i was tempted to sweep it under the rug because his life’s work helped make me who i am today. .
.
but i can’t do that. and i’m very grateful she brought this issue to my attention. the world of fashion—and the people who built it—mean so much to me, and because of that, i will not feign ignorance about its flaws. when you truly love something, you should want to see it for what it really is. or, who he really is. the man who brought chanel back to life in the 80s is the same one who dismissed sexual harassment & assault as part of a model’s job description. the designer who helped propel the career of cindy crawford is the same one who did not believe curvy women had a place in fashion.
.
i honestly don’t know what to think about him anymore. it’s not as if he deserves to be lumped into the same group as harvey weinstein, but i can’t say that i see him with the same admiration as i used to either. even though it stung to dive into the controversial side of karl’s legacy, i’m glad i did because at least i’m not fooling myself. at least, i can see the man for who he was—flaws and all.

text:
olha que bacana essa iniciativa! com tantos casos de violência contra mulher, um bar em canoas, no rio grande do sul (rs), oferece um drink falso, que pode ser "pedido" caso alguma mulher esteja passando por uma situação indesejada no encontro ou se sentindo ameaçada.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
o cartaz explica que basta ir até a área do bar e solicitar a bebida 'la penha'. ao fazer o pedido, a bartender irá chamar alguém do bar para acompanhar a mulher até o carro, uber ou táxi. dependendo do caso, até mesmo a polícia poderá ser acionada. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
e o cartaz que divulga a bebida ainda reforça o apoio às mulheres. "não se cale. não tenha medo. você não está sozinha. estamos aqui para te apoiar".
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

featured in march 2019 edition of instyle magazine.
the academy awards (the oscars) will be held this sunday. the time’s up movement began as the ‘’me too” movement (which originally was started by tarana burke) but because of the hashtag 
#metoo from numerous women ‘tweeting’ accusations towards harvey weinstein of sexual assault. time’s up has raised millions of dollars to support women involved in such organizations as: national farmworkers alliance, united for respect, united food and commercial workers, unite here labor union, lideres compesinas, & national domestic worker’s alliance. equal  pay, a safe working environment, are supported financially as well as by advocacy publicly by today’s ‘hollywood ‘.

text:
#wednesdaywisdom 
sometimes we see what other people are doing and we think, wow they're happy, they're successful, they've got it all figured out... i'm going to do what they're doing! and you may try it for a while and then you don't see the same results and now you're feeling worse about yourself. the problem is, if you don't truly have a passion for it then you will not be happy. it doesn't matter how great of an idea or opportunity it is, if its not for you then it's just not for you. when you find what you're really passionate about, you will know it! you will feel excited and scared, and you'll be looking at things differently. you'll enjoy the journey rather than just rushing to get to your destination. it's great to have people that we look up to and are inspired by, but you don't have to do exactly what they do, maybe instead follow their attitude and drive on chasing their goals and dreams. .
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
meza ashenafi was appointed as a head of ethiopia’s supreme court. before being appointed as a head of ethiopia’s supreme court, ashenafi was a judge on ethiopia’s high court and an adviser to a commission that writes ethiopia’s constitution. because of her firm belief in representation, ashenafi founded the first ethiopian women lawyers association and contributed in the establishment of ethiopia’s first women’s bank: enat bank. from all of her important court cases, ashenafi is famously known for a case that banned kidnapped girls be forced into marriage. because of the attention her case received, it was turned into an ethiopian film called difert. difret was executively produced by angelina jolie. although ashenafi helped to outlaw the tradition that causes kidnapped girls to be forced into marriage, problems similar to ashenafi’s well-known case is still prevalent. across ethiopia, 41% of girls are married off as children and 16% of them before their 15th birthday. despite the change, abduction and forced marriage still occurs in ethiopia. to be infact, in some southern part of ethiopia, one in six girls are abducted into marriage. sign the petition to prevent girls being married at a young age. sign the petition to prove assault is a crime, not a culture.  #metooethiopa #grlpwr  #ethiopia #africa #metoo #girlsrun #it’stime #let’sfight #women #2019 #blackhistory
#ethiopianhistory

text:
the newseum and freedom forum institute announce the award recipients of the fourth annual free expression awards. the free expression awards convene thought leaders, policymakers and philanthropists to recognize individuals for their courageous acts of, and contributions to, free and fearless expression. 
the 2019 honorees are: founder of the ‘me too.’ movement @taranajaneen; academy award nominee and emmy, bafta and peabody award winner @ava; cbs news foreign correspondents elizabeth palmer, debora patta and holly williams; @bobbyberk, @karamo, @tanfrance, @antoni and @jvn, who together co-host the popular @netflix television series, @queereye; and judy woodruff, anchor and managing editor of @newshour.

these influential supporters of the first amendment work tirelessly to enhance free speech, freedom of the press, religious freedom and free expression in arts and entertainment. the event will be hosted by @katiecouric.

to learn more about #freeexpression19, click the link in our bio.
.

text:
"you're so strong"//
//
sometimes it's hard.  people think i have my shit together because i am always smiling, and i guess i do to a certain extent, we all do. but it's a continous day to day battle with myself against sadly, members of my family who have never wanted me to achieve in life since the day i was born, and whom have worked hard to fill my mind with self doubt and a lack of confidence. it worked for a significant portion of my life, but alot of my teenage years have been spent breaking down these mental barriers of self doubt whilst at the same time mourning the death of the only person who ever held my hand, who reassured me of my capabilities and potential in life and made me feel good about myself. i try not to rely on people for happiness anymore. i rely on allah first and foremost and then myself. it's difficult but i am getting there. these last few years have made me realise 1) my true capabilities in life: mentally, emotionally and physically and 2) it is not selfish to put yourself first. //
//
2018 so far has been such a blessed year and i hope it continues to be this blessed. alhamdulillah. all praise is due to allah.//
//

text: let me share my story really quick. last february i was sexually assaulted. it sent me into a tailspin of dark days and even darker nights. my granny used to always tell me that no matter how bad shit is you can find light in every dark day. i couldn’t find any for almost a year. i couldn’t paint i couldn’t move forward. surprisingly my assault forced me to deal with things from my childhood like speaking my truth and confronting my abuser from child hood also. speak your truth you will heal even if it doesn’t seem like it. don’t lose a year like i did. find your peace because you are nothing short of a survivor!!!! i am a sexual survivor not a victim. #artnobart #sundaze614 #localdope #ampartistry #theoriginalampartistry #blackartist #paintislife #acrylicpainting #asseenincolumbus #614artists #undergroundarts #supportyourlocals #blackartsupport #cashapp #artistsoninstagram #likeforlike #share #blackgirlmagic #like #share #tagsomeone #shaderoom #artlife #artnation #printerslife #ohioartist #canvaspainting  #lgbtartist #abusesurvivor #metoo #speaktruth

text:
it’s time to stop saying ‘make sure they rape someone else ’ with our actions. we teach girls to watch their drinks at all times, to always have a buddy, to never walk alone at night, but we never teach not to rape. there will always be a potential victim more drunk, more alone or more vulnerable. there will always be someone who did not watch their drink, who didn’t have a buddy, who did walk alone, and if they were raped? it is not their fault. it is the fault of the rapist for committing the crime. it’s time we start saying ‘don’t rape’ in what we teach as well as what we say. and we must hold rapists accountable in a society all to willing to turn a blind eye. 
https://www.psychologytoday.com/…/teaching-our-sons-not-rape

text:
feel your feels.

since our deepest traumas are imbedded in our guts and muscles, to free ourselves we must free our bodies. -

from infancy we are fed ideas of what strength is... "toughen up", "keep it together", "get over it". when we cut ourselves off from fully feeling it's like slamming on the gas and breaks at the same time.  this is one example of how illness can manifest in our bodies. -

on the deepest level, change always involves the body. - - take a moment to ask where these uncomfortable feelings live in your body? - - acknowledge and thank them for their positive intentions. - - soften your body, breathe, and let yourself feel.

text:
hi dont steal my things please. i know that should be common sense but some people still do that. thanks + love you
(transcription) 
she is
the morning sun rising up from hell
the birds that sing a beautiful song
the warm, gritty sand on the soles of my feet
the tang of cold, refreshing lemonade
the semicolon that kept my sentence going
the interruption in my thoughts from day to day
the light at the end of my tunnel of a life
the beauty found in the heart of a forest
the calm beating of the waves against the shore
the oxygen in my lungs
the epitome of everything wonderful in life
everything i’ve ever needed.

text:
here’s my sonnet. lexi really encouraged me to finish this. i’d read one she wrote and i guess it really just pushed me to complete mine.
(transcription)
my sad secret is still silently stuck
it is an animal that is not tame
sitting in mud i was a sitting duck
my hunter had a gun with perfect aim

unimaginable fear was with me
as i silently screamed night after night 
my door was locked and no one had a key
i was helpless, couldn’t put up a fight 
my family was completely blind to it
diaries filled with hope that it will stop
i definitely couldn’t take another hit 
i was a storm with tears that were raindrops

seven months later, my secret is free
it’s escaped confinement, it’s glad to flee

text:
this ones called “the metaphorical truth” different aspects of my life told by metaphors (transcription) 
the metaphorical truth
i drowned in a sea of grief
my happiness was very brief

my rollercoaster of emotions broke down
i no longer felt like i wanted to drown

my minds storms shook the ocean of my sleep
i couldn’t escape, i was in too deep

in a sea of nameless faces
i was one of the lost traces

my wheels of justice turn as fast as molasses 
i was blind to your hate and deprived of glasses

you cut me down with your piercing words
soon my mental health left like a migrating bird

aaron came along - a rope dropped down from heaven
it should’ve happened that same day - instead it took seven

i’ve heard that words are the weapons with which we wound
and i couldn’t find that to be more true

when you threatened me, your eyes were icy
i knew you deserved to be a detainee

parents are supposed to be the sturdy branches from which their children bloom
but i guess your branches broke cause your children are now doomed

text:
good morning guys ☀️
i decided you guys deserved an update. (original in the last slide)
transcription: hey, how’s it goin? i haven’t wrote here in awhile
i was goin’ 90 and everything fell apart by the mile
up until november i was feelin’ suicidal
heavy
every way i know how to cope would end up bein deadly
it seemed like everyone was fake or eventually left me
i was thinkin of those pill bottles and what would happen if they were empty
i tried talking to a counselor but she didn’t really get me
i wanted to be dead so bad i didn’t care, i was ready
i looked for comfort in food and late night trips to the fridge
but my life just got worse with everything that i 
did
nothing was getting better, who am i to kid? 
i wasted all my time hiding out in my room
spent so much of it in my bed it started feeling like a tomb
one day i decided that i really need to fix this
i got out of my godforsaken bed and went outside with a few friends
i hadn’t stepped foot out of the house since the summer
i said i was always busy and used school as my cover
but that day i learned that’s it’s good to do something new
because on that day, the universe gave me you.

text:
i’ve spent significant moments on mountaintops. the valleys make me question what i learned up there. when i was 16, the cause i would love to die for gripped my heart. and i vowed to die daily for it, til i do walk to brighter shores. 
when i say that i am pro-life, what does that mean? i could have a really long talk with you over this, but never over social media. this is just where i share my heart. to me, being pro-life never means being against pro-choice. it means that i am pro-every-woman, man, girlfriend, boyfriend, and partner; every sister, daughter, aunt, niece, mother, grandmother, child, father, son, grandfather, brother, uncle, nephew, & especially, especially those who don’t know yet which of those they could ever fit into. no matter what age, no matter whether in the womb or out, i am pro-all-of-them. i am pro-life because i am for talking about hiv. i believe in educating both young girls & boys about local crisis stabilization units. i believe you should never yell at a child without seeing if something in you made them cry, and then if someone made you cry, too. i believe in forgiveness, first of all, of self. i would hold a tender young mother close if she came near me with tears on her face and a small belly starting to show, before i would ever tell her to just have the baby. i believe in education. i don’t believe in any church that thinks picketing damnation & eternal hellfire at any eternal soul is any way to save any life. that’s called choosing suicide. remember that suicide still happens far more often than school shootings. let’s remember that the number is not the issue. the issue is not an answer. the issue is the question we must ask our hearts- “did i love?” and to me, the core of it all is not whether i am pro-life or pro-choice or pro-gender-equality or pro-transsexuals or pro any gay bar ever. i am pro-human. and to me, that means if i ever get kicked out of any “church” for my beliefs, i already have been told to dust my feet off & keep walking. if i had ended up pregnant in that alley *or that “church”*,
i would have really struggled too. i choose life because i choose you.

text:
with the advent of the #metoo movement, much is being written about women’s empowerment and the “new” ways in which women are finding their voice. perhaps this is striking a chord deep within you. maybe you find yourself wondering how we’ve arrived at a place and time where it feels somehow radical just to speak your own truth. 
this class discusses how we can reconnect with the goddess in daily life to empower ourselves, our families and our communities. 
heatherleigh navarre has been studying goddess practices for over a decade, and has traveled to crete, malta, france, italy and spain to experience and learn more about the places and traditions that were sacred in the time of the goddess. 
book online or call 248-548-1415 to hold your spot. ✨

theoretically, 
mathematically even

or twice

would not last forever. 
it is here:

the first

whisper
into every corner of your life: 
thank you

text: the families at the border shouldn't pay for syncing to tech. if your not outraged. i need to say, all perspectives aside, it's wrong. they're here. in the united states of america. seperated, no genuine guidance. treated as less than human, being pushed around by people they don't know and might not speak the same language. to be released into the united states of america, whether it be shelters, adoption, ect.; not certain. not ever; personally in my opinion would i say they came to hurt us. promise of land of the free; failed while seeking asylum. we've had decent border security in previous years, lifes always dangerous. republican, democrat whatever, you don't get to ignore this issue. kinda like me my independence i've worked for you hate, you don't like strong women, you like easy. do you want them dead? is that how we deal with eachother? when a life is shaken that hard without reasonable comprehension, no foundation, might not be able to spell survival. those kids and families did not show up for trouble, just a better future. some will be ok, and hopefully im wrong with this next statement, yet everyone of every identifier has the potential to be...destructive, self included. the issues they face everyday, will be expanded, throughout the country, without warning, without guidance, released into whatever society they're damned to; no longer reasonable sized issues they carry. will you consider them worth acknowledging? will it be too late? are you gonna cry about deserving a chance to explain yourself for ignoring the good in them from the start? at this point, they're going to need good role models of their own culture, lots of guidance, some skills to ignore the ignorance with. they're going to live here. are you comfortable? they aren't. some proud country, can't even listen to elder countries, learning to break social barriers and teach languages in elementary. america wants its independence from the countries our ancestors were from; yet can't stand the thought of granting independence, cultural freedoms, to minorities and women. actively listen and value lives of those around you like your own. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors

text:
2: dancing
pictured: tapestry hanging over my bed •
confiding in my friends and family (and even the unknown internet strangers) about my assault freed me in a way i didn't know i needed. i felt a type of relief i've never felt before - i even felt the tiniest bit of, dare i say... joy. i mean shit, i even danced in the kitchen when i was cooking yesterday! talk about straight out of a (fucked-up) rom-com.
•
but then, when i was dancing along to nathaniel rateliff alone in my kitchen, i stopped and asked myself - "should i be doing this? should i be feeling this? shouldn't i be "recovering" or coping or grieving or whatever the fuck a "victim" is supposed to do?" •
read the full entry at foundblogchicago.com

text: a estátua que retrata o famoso beijo de um marinheiro com uma mulher nos eua, flagrado e eternizado como uma das cenas marcantes do fim da segunda guerra mundial, recebeu uma pichação contra assédio após a morte do americano. o homem da foto, george mendonsa morreu no início desta semana, aos 95 anos. um dia depois, a estátua "rendição incondicional, da cidade de sarasota, na flórida, foi vista com a inscrição "#metoo" na perna de greta zimmer friedman, a mulher beijada. a polícia local estimou em r$ 3,7 mil o custo da restauração da obra pichada. embora o beijo de george mendonsa e greta zimmer friedman tenha ficado famoso como uma cena de felicidade e comemoração pelo fim da guerra, depois que o japão se rendeu aos eua, alguns passaram a interpretar o gesto como um beijo forçado, sem o consentimento da mulher. em 2005, a americana destacou ao veteran's history project que foi "agarrada" pelo marinheiro, mas classificou o beijo como um ato de alívio pelo fim do conflito. ela morreu em 2016. 😮 #jornaloglobo #historia #usnavy #segundaguerra #memoria #eua 📸: polícia de sarasota/reuters

text:
nella nostra vita molto spesso
ci hanno derise.
ci hanno offese.
ci hanno svilite.
ci hanno sottovalutate.
ci hanno umiliate.

molto spesso nella nostra vita
abbiamo avuto il coraggio di reagire.
abbiamo avuto la forza di parlare.
abbiamo avuto la speranza di un aiuto.

molto spesso però molte donne non hanno avuto nessuna possibilità.

non siamo oggetti senza anima.
siamo anime con un cuore.
.
.

🙋🏾‍♀️ deadline approaching 🙋🏽‍♀️ final applications for our sisters in strength pilot program are due friday, february 22nd by 5pm.

are you a teen passionate about ending sexual and gender-based violence?

the firecracker foundation is recruiting self-identified survivors of sexual violence and allies to survivors of sexual violence who are in 10th or 11th grade to its new program, sisters in strength - lansing.

individuals who apply should share a vision for ending violence, desire to build sisterhood/siblinghood (community), and willingness to advocate for change.

sis is one of two pilot #metooteen programs in the country.

link to the application in our bio.

text:
fun fact: every time the c word is uttered, a feminist gets their wings. 🦋
.
.
today was my last long run before my half. i’ve been running the indoor track at my rec center because there’s snow and ice on the ground. and the indoor track is a happening spot for elderly folks. they walk, i run, so i lap them a lot. and every time i do, i feel the little old ladies look at me with a sense of awe. and i realize that when they were my age, women’s lib was just happening. teachers and nurses were still required to wear skirts. women weren’t wearing leggings and raising kids and owning businesses very often. .
.
so every time i passed these women on the track, i’d send them a silent message of gratitude for paving the way in whatever way they did for my daughters generation. .
.
i know i’m “just” running a half marathon. but i’m doing it dressed like a princess, and it wasn’t that long ago that a 39 year old woman running a half marathon dressed like a princess was a ridiculous idea. .
.
so hildegard emma tonk monska, i am running this race in honor of you. thank you for not flinching when i told you hope chests were bullshit. i love you, grandma. and for my mom, pamela marie for never once insinuating that i couldn’t do anything i wanted to do. and for my daughter, emma delphine, because whatever she wants to do is just perfect. i’m running for everyone who has been told they’re too fat, or not curvy enough. too smart, not smart enough. too loud, too quiet. too ugly, too pretty. you are not too much and you have always been enough. don’t forget that. we will smash the patriarchy, one tiny step at a time.
.
.
#motherrunner #momlife #riotgrrl #rundisney #halfmarathontraining #fempreneur #feminist #wegirlscandoanything #whoruntheworld #disneyprincess #metoo #smashthepatriarchy

text:
trigger warning:addiction 
if you’ve struggled with addiction, this will probably hit you super hard. 
i’ve been struggling with these ideas for years, so i took a bit of my own advice and decided to write about it and share it. you know display some of that vulnerability i’m always on about.

it’s about how much potential i’ve seen wasted and how much beauty could have been created by all the addicts i’ve ever known,  had that will been bent to creative and it self destructive means.

if you vibe with this please share or let me know what you think. if i can help even one person with this, then it was all worth it. “the tragic hero psychosis’’ you’re the hero, in another life. the potential profound and ground deep into the ashtray like so much ash. 
another dead cigarette cooked to the filter, added to the pile. the very same energy could have started fires that would have changed the world as you know it. 
but i’m that quiet moment when you hear the voice inside you that asks. “what might i have been” 
so it always begins, these many broken pieces of mirror reflecting my own bad luck back at me.

or so the weak parts of me say. the breakable parts.

i will break all that is breakable inside myself, till i find that core of iron. 
and once i find that dark oxidized rusty hunk inside of me. 
once i’ve burned away all potential i feared i had in the first place. 
i will begin to reforge this iron. 
the stone cold lump in my gut told me that i had found it, that i had finally struck the part that has hard... and strong. 
for only the hard and the strong may call themselves weavers of their own fate.

i lament weeping away the last bits of me left to care about this wretch inside my mind. the coward who says i cannot make this happen. the one who says “what if” and “it’s not possible” i weep that it’s still small voice is so strong. 
that this still small voice has crumbled so much potential into its hands and watched it fall away, empty husks in the wind.

my identity so wrapped into this tragic hero’s ideal of beauty, twisted though it is, that i have heard and seen and participated in acts that would cause most strong men ....... cont below

text:
you can now preorder my memoir 
never without love 
on amazon.
click the link in my bio.
.
.
“both charming and powerful, this memoir unfolds the story of a young girl born in iran who eventually triumphs over sexism and abuse to become a successful woman and mother in canada. the book opens with a dramatic account of a terrible accident that leaves a young child with burn scars all over her chest. this scarring has a profound effect on the girl's life. yet, despite this accident, the narrator's childhood is rich and blessed in many ways. the family circle is extensive and the relationships, especially with the wonderful baba (her father) and her spirited cousin fereshteh, are both protective and complex. the narrator travels from qazvin, an ancient capital of the persian empire, to remote mountain villages, to the glittering capital of tehran with its cafés, dance clubs, fancy boutiques and lush parks, to a villa on the caspian sea, as well as to the "tin town" of halaby abad in southern tehran and to the rice paddies where women do backbreaking work for next to nothing in wages. in doing so, she deftly handles a minefield of politics, from the regime of the shah to the foreign interests of british and americans, to street marches and protests, to the installation of the ayatollah khomeini and the islamic republic. a beloved uncle is murdered by the revolutionary guards and the narrator's own marriage to a man of the bahai faith is illegal. sexual politics and women's rights are addressed throughout the memoir from the persian custom of khastegari, to the stripping of women's rights under the islamic republic to domestic abuse in canada.”
.
.

text: little house on the prairie. well not really. this is the house where i spent 9 years in canada growing up before i jumped on the back of a motorbike at age 14 and never looked back.  my brother sent this to me just the other day. it brings back a wave of memories. i have only been back twice to those roads and once in those walls since. yes there were good times, long walks on dusty summer roads, christmas morning, first kiss in the closet, wonder women in the out house ( don’t ask 😂😂). if the walls could talk they would cry. i shared with ross and the kids the funny moments in those walls it made me feel like not all was lost. on that land where i would lay in the fields in summer awaiting for the ground to swallow me whole. the window i would sit at and look at the road forward. note to self.  be really aware of what you thinking about as life has it. life happens. what you think about becomes.  now i look at this snap and say “ you have come along way baby “ ❤️. this summer i am so looking forward to going back and lay in that same  field with my family and instead of it swallowing me. i will stand up. i will brush myself off and say “ you got this girl”. ❤️. the past is in behind for a reason.  it does not dictate your future. it is just a glimpse of how far you have journeyed. #memories #family #lifeofmom #inspirationalquotes #lifeofmom #metoo

text:
“there is little hope for justice through an official appeal, and i will definitely not be making any appeals for clemency,

a crimean tatar leader, ilmi umerov refused to seek clemency in 2017 after being sentenced to two years in prison. umerov was tried for comments made to a crimean tatar television station last year in which he decried the 2014 annexation of the territory. he has been diagnosed with stage three parkinson’s disease, has type 2 diabetes and underwent a heart operation several years ago and his lawyer, mark feygin, seriously doubts his ability to withstand the 2 year prison term,

the european union called umerov's sentencing a “serious violation of his human rights” and “another example of persecution of the crimean tatar community, and a further and clear illustration of the severe deterioration of human rights on the crimean peninsula.

during the 2nd world war, stalin had deported the whole crimean population, only in 1988 were they given the right of return. umerov was fighting the cause, and now he is fighting for his life, 
help better the world and share this post ❤️
#crimea #russia #ukraine #prison #likeforlikes #followforfollowback #world #sentences #unfair #cool #awareness #metoo

text:
is it ok... if i'm vulnerable and transparent... if i confess the struggle is real... if i say the internal battle of the mind never ceases within me... that my ptsd gets the best of me at times and i want to runaway from my ownself... just to get away from the voices in my head that say........................ the weeping... the sorrow... the self deprecating... the things i say about myself to myself i'd never even say to my worst enemy... wounds so deep that it will take a miracle to be healed... father, the thorn in my side that i endure is has a hold of me and trying to consume me with its piercing jabs of past hurts... but god... i know you see me... i know you are hearing my cries... i know that in jesus' name there is deliverance... so i wait... and i wait.... the word is my defense sharper than any two edged sword... made of dust and dirt i know where i came from and where i was rescued out of... so i wait... this is a redemptive love story and for glory of the father that even the most deplorable things in life can be used to bring him praise... so in the waiting i will praise the  lord most high... because he is a good good father in good times and in bad... he is a good good father... ❤
#selfie #selflove #thestruggleisreal #recovered #bulemic anorexic #eatingdisorder #ptsd #overcomer #jesusgypsy #hotmesssavedbygrace #metoo

text:
still living book; a victimized man’s journey by best selling author marcel anderson: 
just another ordinary day quickly transformed into what could have been the last day of my life. things were going great; i was on the verge of getting the job i wanted, i had launched the accelerating men mentoring program and i was working on music for my album, when one day i was attacked, blindfolded, tied up, and brutalized for several hours. even with severe damage to my internal organs, i somehow walked away from that situation and was eventually forced to deal with my life from a new perspective. “what if i am not physically able to do the things i once did?” “should i get revenge for what was done to me? “how do i move on from here?” “how can i trust anyone again?” “why am i living?” “what is my purpose? “with my book, still living; a victimized man’s journey, i share my story to help you understand that no matter what has happened in your life, you are purposed to live. this book is designed to bring healing, salvation, and deliverance from the bondage that the adversary tries to place us in through guilt, shame, difficult circumstances, and fear.
visit www.acceleratingmen.org & download your copy today. book marcel anderson for your next event.
target: sexual assault surviors

text:
people keep asking me why i stayed with my abuser after being verbally, physically and psychologically abused daily. once the authorities got involved and he was removed from the home by the department of family and children in new jersey, why didnt i leave my marriage? why would i do that? i still don't know. maybe i used to believe crocodile tears like i got when the cops arrested him and he left me this note. but hell no, i don't now. this is my platform for talking about abuse and i will use it even if it goes against the orders of a system that shackles my voice and rewards my abuser. kathryn and renee were conceived after the assault that i posted previously. i left their father when i was 4 months pregnant after he was allowed back into the home and started to abuse me again. i went home to potomac. thankgod for my girls. i made bad decisions for myself. but my children would not have been born without the bad decisions i made. its fucked up. i think of this every day. it is a shame i carry with me every day. and i have lied about it for too long. no more lies, no more hiding. this is my #metoo #proudmom 
i am an instagram author and boston university college of communications grad.

text:
#metoo and #timesup are more than hashtags. they are movements to hold sexual harassers accountable and to deliver justice to victims and survivors of sexual abuse and harassment. while the call for justice for women who have been sexually abused and harassed is long overdue, the response to that call is far different than the response to those calling for racial justice.

this is well-documented. but white people not only don’t want to pay, they don’t even want to think about reparations. for decades, former u.s. rep. john conyers (the michigan democrat who resigned after sexual harassment allegations) sponsored a bill to study the issue of reparations for slavery. it’s never made it to the floor of the u.s. house.

black people simply do not see the same response to our complaints as we do when the victims of injustice include white people. take the way our society treats the victims and survivors of sexual abuse and harassment. from hollywood and the u.s. congress to prestigious schools, survivors of sexual abuse and harassment are demanding a reckoning and, in some cases, receiving compensation for their suffering.

yet, the same public outcry that has ignited institutional reckonings about sexual abuse and harassment is mute about concurrent racial abuse that includes rampant police killings, mass incarceration, housing discrimination, income inequality, and white nationalism and supremacy. the list goes on and on.
we must pay attention to the victims of organized racism in schools, media networks, and all workplaces and public spaces. the only way for it to stop is for there to be real accountability for the practice of racism in all its forms. and we know that america learns its lessons best when there is a price to pay. when it hits the pocketbook, we see real change. the only way to stop the ongoing poison of racism is through reparations. while reparations will not erase the ramifications of generations of racist assaults, they would at once compensate victims and educate perpetrators of racism.

reparations can come in many forms just ask.

text:
oh i’ve seen the raised eyebrows, the rolling eyes, heard the tutting and clocked the shaking of the heads.... and i’m not even a mum!

i feel for every mother out there who is apparently a complete free-for-all on public judgement.

yes, women get angry. yes, women get angry at their kids. frankly i’m sure children need to see a little anger or hear a raised voice now and again.

but actually, what i think really doesn’t matter.... and neither does what you think. every parent has the right to bring up their child in the best way they see fit. subject to no abuse or harm coming to that child, i doubt you or i really know enough to judge that mum who just shouted at her son to stop licking the lamp post. or her daughter to stop eating mud off her shoe.

so let’s put the eye brows down, chill the the tutting and leave mum to decide how to be a good parent.

#feminist #smashthepatriarchy #equality #mum #mother #children #parenting #angry #quotes #feminism #mumlife #kids #women #ladies #metoo #empoweringwomen #empowerment #positivevibes #parents #emotions

yes, women get angry. yes, women get angry at their kids. frankly i’m sure children need to see a little anger or hear a raised voice now and again.

but actually, what i think really doesn’t matter.... and neither does what you think. every parent has the right to bring up their child in the best way they see fit. subject to no abuse or harm coming to that child, i doubt you or i really know enough to judge that mum who just shouted at her son to stop licking the lamp post. or her daughter to stop eating mud off her shoe.

so let’s put the eye brows down, chill the the tutting and leave mum to decide how to be a good parent.

text:
“politics of the mind” continues! this blog is an exploration of our political structure as a metaphor for how we use our mind (government) against our true nature (the people). this is part 3: the judicial branch, and perhaps the most challenging of them all for it speaks into things we hold righteously close to our hearts— justice, freedom, and the pursuit of happiness. if you missed them, parts 1 & 2 are in my last two posts. enjoy!
⚖️
the judicial branch springs forth in our mind but with a very different version of our lady of justice prevailing. her sword of reason is dulled by duality, her scale is skewed toward injustice, and her blindfold is woven by the frayed heartstrings of a victim. for she, though beautiful as ever, is born in our heartbreak.
⚖️
before our heartbreak, we had no concept of injustice. life was simply cause and effect with ourselves at the helm of change. though the seas of life could turn at any moment, we held our authority to navigate a new course of action.
⚖️
yet when we fell into the heartbreak of 'i am not', we were thrown off-balance by the disconnect from our personal power. the responsibility for our creation shifted to outside forces and we traded our power for the role of victim, perceiving life through a now wounded sense of justice— look at what they do to me.
⚖️
the scales were further weighted by the subtle awareness that we had in fact betrayed ourselves by giving our power away, thus adding the burden of guilt and the hesitancy of self-doubt. we no longer quite trusted our power, and the role of victim became a comfortable, albeit small, refuge.
⚖️
until we find the wisdom to forgive ourselves and return to the 'i am', we are partially paralyzed by the mistrust in our personal power and blinded by the wound of injustice. though our true nature is emotionally motivated to rebalance the scale of justice, as long we view life through the eyes of the victim, we will continually perceive injustice; as long as we falsely perceive injustice, we will continue to serve dependence rather than independence, and there is no greater disrespect to our freedom than that of false dependence.
⚖️
(continued in comments)

text:
who you are, where you are, as you are, and no matter where you are is okay. you can take those pieces and have peace with it. you weren't put here to suffer. life is a process, a journey. you have a reason to be at peace; even if it simply means to stay looking and feeling good.💁🏽‍♀️pay attention to the good that you are, the good that you have, the good that you've done. you have a reason to celebrate you. be what you want to get out of the world, a place of peace. don't lose your balance. practice the process of peace. obtaining this, obtaining your healing doesn't require anything you don't already have. you are enough ‼️always have been 😌.
peace and light, queens!✨
love, ✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿 📸: @thebrvery, july '18
